584506849/ref=cm_sw_em_r_mt_dp_U_9mrKEbNZC02K1 |website=Amazon|date=March 2009}}</ref>, Dave Mark detailed how to mentally think of behavior in terms of math including such things as response curves (converting changing input variables to output variables). He and Kevin Dill went on to give many of the early lectures on utility theory at the AI Summit of the annual [[Game Developers Conference]] (GDC) in San Francisco including \"Improving AI Decision Modeling Through Utility Theory\" in 2010<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mark|first1=Dave|last2=Dill|first2=Kevin|title=Improving AI Decision Modeling Through Utility Theory|url=https://gdcvault.com/play/1012410/Improving-AI-Decision-Modeling-Through|website=GDC Vault|date=2010}}</ref> and \"Embracing the Dark Art of Mathematical Modeling in AI\" in 2012<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mark|first1=Dave|last2=Dill|first2=Kevin|title=Embracing the Dark Art of Mathematical Modeling in AI|url=https://gdcvault.com/play/1015683/Embracing-the-Dark-Art-of|website=GDC Vault|date=2012}}</ref>. These lectures served to inject utility AI as a commonly referred to architecture alongside finite state machines (FSMs), behavior trees, and planners.\n\n=== A \"Utility System\" ===\n\nWhile the work of Richard Evans, and subsequent AI programmers on the Sims franchise such as David \"Rez\" Graham<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=David \"Rez\"|title=An Introduction to Utility Theory|url=http://www.gameaipro.com/GameAIPro/GameAIPro_Chapter09_An_Introduction_to_Utility_Theory.pdf|website=GameAIPro|date=September 2013}}</ref> were heavily based on utility AI, Dave Mark and his co-worker from ArenaNet, Mike Lewis, went on to lecture about a full stand-alone architecture he had developed, the Infinite Axis Utility System (IAUS) at the AI Summit during the 2015 GDC<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mark|first1=Dave|last2=Lewis|first2=Mike|title=Building a Better Centaur: AI at Massive Scale|url=https://gdcvault.com/play/1021848/Building-a-Better-Centaur-AI|website=GDC Vault|date=2015}}</ref>. The IAUS was designed to be a data-driven, self-contained architecture that, once hooked up to the inputs and outputs of the game system, did not require much programming support. In a way, this made it similar to behavior trees and planners where the reasoner (what makes the decisions) was fully established and it was left to the development team to add behaviors into the mix as they saw fit.\n\n=== Utility with other Architectures ===\n\nAdditionally, rather than a stand-alone architecture, other people discussed methods of incorporating utility calculations into existing architectures. Bill Merrill wrote an segment in the book, ''Game AI Pro''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rabin|first1=Steve|title=Game AI Pro|url=https://www.amazon.com/Game-AI-Pro-Collected-Professionals-ebook/dp/B00UV90K50/|website=Amazon|date=September 2013}}</ref>, entitled \"Building Utility Decisions into Your Existing Behavior Tree\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Merrill|first1=Bill|title=Building Utility Decisions into Your Existing Behavior Tree|url=http://www.gameaipro.com/GameAIPro/GameAIPro_Chapter10_Building_Utility_Decisions_into_Your_Existing_Behavior_Tree.pdf|website=GameAIPro|date=September 2013}}</ref> with examples of how to re-purpose selectors in BTs to use utility-based math. This made for a powerful hybrid that kept much of the popular formal structure of behavior trees but allowed for some of the non-brittle advantages that utility offered.\n\n==See Also==\n* [[Behavior_tree_(artificial_intelligence,_robotics_and_control)|Behavior Trees]]\n* [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|Video game AI]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Game artificial intelligence]]\n", "name_user": "InnocuousFox", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eA \"Utility System\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utility_system"}
{"title_page": "James J. Jeffries", "text_new": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{refimprove|date = February 2019}}\n{{other people|James Jeffries}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n|name=James J. Jeffries\n|image=James J Jeffries.jpg\n|realname=James Jackson Jeffries\n|nickname=[[Boilermaker|The Boilermaker]]<br>Big Jeff<br>Big Jim<br>Jim\n|weight=[[Heavyweight]]\n|height=6 ft 1+1/2 in\n|reach=76+1/2 in\n|nationality=United States\n|birth_date={{birth date|1875|04|15|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Carroll, Ohio]], [[United States|US]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1953|03|03|1875|04|15|mf=y}}\n|death_place=[[Burbank, California]], [[United States|US]]\n|style=[[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n|total=24\n|wins=19\n|KO=16\n|losses=1\n|draws=2\n|no contests=2\n}}\n'''James Jackson''' \"'''Jim'''\" '''Jeffries''' (April 15, 1875 \u2013 March 3, 1953) was an [[Americans|American]] professional [[Boxing|boxer]] and World Heavyweight Champion.\n\nHe was known for his enormous strength and stamina. Using a technique taught to him by his trainer, former [[Welterweight]] and [[Middleweight]] Champion [[Tommy Ryan]], Jeffries fought out of a crouch with his left arm extended forward. He was able to absorb tremendous punishment while wearing his opponents down. A natural left-hander, he possessed one-punch knockout power in his left hook, and brawled his way to the top of the rankings. He is perhaps most famous for being United States \"Great White Hope\", since the nation expected him to come out of his retirement to beat the African-American boxer [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]], who was at the time the Heavyweight Champion.<ref>https://search.alexanderstreet.com/preview/work/bibliographic_entity%7Cvideo_work%7C1789067?ssotoken=anonymous</ref>\n\nJeffries stood {{convert|6|ft|1+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}} tall and weighed {{convert|225|lb}} in his prime. He could run {{convert|100|yd|m}} in just over ten seconds, and could high jump over {{convert|6|ft|cm}}.\n\n==Early life==\nJeffries moved with his family from their Ohio farm to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] at age seven.<ref>http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/oldtimer/jeffries.html</ref> He worked for a while as a [[boilermaker]] before going into boxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=1409&more=1|title=WardDawsonSDown2|author=ES Boxing|work=Boxing News 24/7}}</ref> In later life, \"The Boilermaker\" was one of his professional nicknames.\n\n==Career==\nAs a powerfully built and athletic teenager, Jeffries boxed as an amateur until age 20, when he started fighting professionally.\n\nIn his third fight, Jeffries knocked out the highly regarded boxer [[Hank Griffin (boxer)|Hank Griffin]] in the fourteenth round. [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]] would subsequently fight Griffin on three separate occasions.\n\nJeffries fought the top heavyweight contender, Gus Ruhlin, to a draw. Ruhlin was knocked down with a brutal punch at the end of the final round and was saved by the bell from being counted out. The decision was met with unfavorable reactions from the audience, many of whom felt Jeffries won.\n\nOn his way to the title in 1898, Jeffries knocked out [[Peter Jackson (boxer)|Peter Jackson]], the great boxer whom [[John L. Sullivan]] had refused to fight, in three rounds. This had been only the second defeat in Jackson's entire career; his first loss was from a four-round fight over thirteen years earlier around the beginning of his career. Jackson retired shortly afterward.\n\nJeffries defeated the formidable Mexican Pete Everett by knockout in only the third round on April 22, 1898.\n\nHis next fight was against the Irishman [[Tom Sharkey]]. The fight went the full twenty rounds and Sharkey was knocked down in the eleventh round. Jeffries won the decision.\n\nAfter defeating the big, fast-moving, sharp-jabbing [[Bob Armstrong (boxer)|Bob Armstrong]], Jeffries had earned the right to challenge for the World Heavyweight Championship.\n\nOn June 9, 1899 in [[Brooklyn, New York]] he defeated [[Bob Fitzsimmons]] by KO in the eleventh round to win the [[Heavyweight]] Championship of the World. That August, he embarked on a tour of [[Europe]], putting on exhibition fights for the fans. Jeffries was involved in several motion pictures recreating portions of his championship fights. Filmed portions of his other bouts and of some of his exhibition matches survive to this day.\n\n===World Heavyweight Champion===\nIn his first title defense, he won a twenty-five-round decision in a rematch over Tom Sharkey.\n\nJeffries set the record for the quickest KO in a Heavyweight title fight ever, which was 55 seconds against Jack Finnegan in his second title defense.\n\nHis next defense was against the former [[Heavyweight]] Champion and legendary technician, [[James J. Corbett]]. Corbett had put up a perfect defense and could have arguably won had the fight gone the distance. However, Corbett was knocked out cold from a left to the jaw in the twenty-third round of the scheduled twenty-five round fight.\n\nJeffries later got the chance to avenge his controversial draw with Gus Ruhlin when he defended his title against him on November 15, 1901. Claims that Ruhlin quit during the fifth round are incorrect. All of the local next-day San Francisco sources agree that Ruhlin's manager, Billy Madden, threw in the towel to retire Gus during the one-minute interval between the fifth and sixth rounds.\n\nAn example of Jeffries' ability to absorb punishment and recover from a severe battering to win a bout came in his rematch for the title with Fitzsimmons, who is regarded as one of the hardest punchers in boxing history. The rematch with Jeffries occurred on July 25, 1902 in [[San Francisco]]. To train for the bout Jeffries' daily training included a {{convert|14|mi|km|sing=on}} run, 2 hours of skipping rope, medicine ball training, 20 minutes sparring on the heavy bag, and at least 12 rounds of sparring in the ring. He also trained in wrestling.\n\nFor nearly eight rounds Fitzsimmons subjected Jeffries to a vicious battering. Jeffries suffered a broken nose, both his cheeks were cut to the bone, and gashes were opened over both eyes. It appeared that the fight would have to be stopped, as blood freely flowed into Jeffries' eyes. Then in the eighth round, Jeffries lashed out with a terrific right to the stomach, followed by a left hook to the jaw which knocked Fitzsimmons unconscious.\n\nJeffries and Corbett met one last time in the ring on August 14, 1903. This time Jeffries was in total control for all ten rounds of the scheduled twenty round bout. Tommy Ryan, Corbett's chief second, threw a large palm-leaf fan into the ring to alert Referee Graney that he should stop the fight.\n\nJeffries had his seventh and final title defense against Canadian Jack Munroe, whom he stopped in only two rounds.\n\nJeffries broke the ribs of three opponents in title fights: [[James J. Corbett|Jim Corbett]], Gus Ruhlin and [[Tom Sharkey]]. Jeffries retired undefeated in May 1905. He served as a referee for the next few years, including the bout in which [[Marvin Hart]] defeated [[Jack Root]] to stake a claim at Jeffries' vacated title. Jeffries had never been knocked down in his prime.\n\nJeffries had likely fought many more bouts than twenty-two at this time. Many of his fights were lost in history. Jeffries, however, had never been defeated before his original retirement.\n\n===Comeback: \"The Fight of the Century\"===\n[[File:Johnson jeff.jpg|left|thumb|200px|James Jeffries during his fight with [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]]]\nOver five years after retiring, Jeffries made a comeback on July 4, 1910 at [[Reno, Nevada]] in a match against champion [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]], who had won the [[Heavyweight]] Championship in 1908 by defeating Canadian champion [[Tommy Burns (boxer)|Tommy Burns]] at [[Rushcutters Bay, New South Wales|Rushcutters Bay]] in Australia. Burns was the first heavyweight champion to fight African-American challengers.\n\nThe media put pressure onto Jeffries and promoters dangled wealth in front of him to take the fight. He finally acquiesced, saying \"I am going into this fight for the sole purpose of proving that a white man is better than a negro.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Zirin |first=Dave|year=2008 |title=\nPeople's History of Sports in the United States: 250 Years of Politics, Protest, People, and Play|publisher=The New Press|page=42|ISBN=1595581006}}</ref> In addition to a guaranteed purse of $40,000 (equivalent to approximately ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|40000|1910|r=0}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}), to woo the ex-champ back into the ring, promoter [[Tex Rickard]] had signed him to a $75,000 personal contract.\n\nAfter a six-year lay-off, the 35-year-old Jeffries was out of shape and had lost most of his muscle. Jeffries weighed over 330 pounds (150&nbsp;kg), while Johnson was in superb physical condition. The ex-champ had to lose 110 pounds to get down to his fighting weight of 226, a Herculean task in the time he had before the fight. Previous Heavyweight Champion [[John L. Sullivan]] (an ethnic Irish American who refused to fight African-American contenders) remarked during an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' that Jeffries' personal doctor was so amazed at Johnson's physical condition that he felt Jeffries could win only if Johnson had a lack of skill on the day. While the media instigated racist remarks about winning the title for whites, Jeffries' final words before the fight were, \"It is my intention to go right after my opponent and knock him out as soon as possible.\" His wife also commented, \"I'm not interested in prizefighting but I am interested in my husband's welfare, I do hope this will be his last fight.\"<ref>[http://www.aolnews.com/2010/07/04/jack-johnson-jim-jeffries-highlighted-u-s-racial-divide/ \"Jack Johnson-Jim Jeffries Fight Highlighted the US Racial Divide\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302193813/http://www.aolnews.com/2010/07/04/jack-johnson-jim-jeffries-highlighted-u-s-racial-divide/ |date=2012-03-02 }}, 4 July 2010, AOL News</ref>\n\n{{YouTube|L1y76L2P-IQ|Motion picture footage}} of Jeffries on the morning of the fight depicts a relaxed man playing with his dog. Ringside seats that had been priced at $50 were being scalped at $125 each (equivalent to approximately ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|125|1910|r=0}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}). More than 1,000 spectators who were unable to get seats in the sold-out arena climbed over the walls to enter.\n\nBefore the fight, which was scheduled for 45 three-minute rounds, famous boxers who had traveled to Reno to witness the contest were introduced to the crowd, including [[Sam Langford]], a black boxer who was unable to secure a title fight, even from Jack Johnson. The greatest applause went to [[Jake Kilrain]], who had battled John L. Sullivan back in the bare-knuckle days.\n\nAt three minutes to one P.M., Johnson entered the ring (his contract provided that he would always be first to enter the ring, to satisfy a superstition of his). The thermometer read 110\u00b0 Fahrenheit, which meant the match would be even more brutal due to heat. Jeffries soon joined Johnson in the ring. Rickard served as referee. (Johnson and Jeffries could not agree on a referee, and Rickard's publicity-minded offers to President [[William Howard Taft]] and writer [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] to serve as referee were declined. Rickard took the position although he had never refereed a prize fight before.)\n\nIn the first three rounds, the boxers sparred to feel each other out. Johnson, having read that no one could tie Jeffries up on the inside due to his power, told the press that not only would he do so, but that he planned to neutralize Jeffries' power by twisting his arms behind him. Toward the end of the fourth round, he did just that, pinning Jeffries' arms in back of him for a moment, but Jeffries broke the clinch. Johnson landed a solid overhand right to Jeffries' head just before the bell.\n\nJohnson began dominating the fight in rounds five through twelve, as his opponent faded in the heat and from Johnson's onslaught. The heat began to get to Johnson, too, by round 13, but he was still the stronger and younger man in the ring. Toward the end of that round, he delivered a right and a right uppercut to Jeffries' head that took their toll. In the next round, Jeffries eluded Johnson, who stalked him all over the ring.\n\nIn round 15, Johnson went after Jeffries and caught him against the ropes with a right upper-cut, followed by three left uppercuts that sent the ex-champ to the canvas for the first time in his career. He could no longer put up a defense and, as Jeffries got up, Johnson hit him with a left hook that sent him to the canvas and through the ropes, putting his torso outside the ring. Helped to his feet by one of his seconds and a fan, as soon as Jeffries was back in the ring he was rushed by Johnson, who knocked him down again with a right to the head. As Rickard moved in to separate the fighters, Jeffries got up, but his manager had entered the ring to stop the fight and save his fighter from being knocked out. Johnson retained the title by a [[technical knockout]].\n\nJohnson later remarked that he knew the fight was over in the 4th round when he landed an uppercut to Jeffries' face and saw the look in his eyes. \"I knew what that look meant,\" he said. \"The old ship was sinking.\" [[John L. Sullivan]] commented for ''[[The New York Times]]'' after the fight that Johnson won deservedly, fairly, and convincingly:\n\n{{quote|The fight of the century is over and a black man is the undisputed champion of the world. It was a poor fight as fights go, this less than 15-round affair between James J. Jeffries and Jack Johnson. Scarcely has there ever been a championship contest that was so one-sided. All of Jeffries much-vaunted condition amounted to nothing. He wasn't in it from the first bell tap to the last \u2026. The negro had few friends, but there was little demonstration against him. (Spectators) could not help but admire Johnson because he is the type of prizefighter that is admired by sportsmen. He played fairly at all times and fought fairly. \u2026 What a crafty, powerful, cunning left hand (Johnson) has. He is one of the craftiest, cunningest boxers that ever stepped into the ring. \u2026 They both fought closely all during the 15 rounds. It was just the sort of fight that Jeffries wanted. There was no running or ducking like Corbett did with me in New Orleans (1892). Jeffries did not miss so many blows, because he hardly started any. Johnson was on top of him all the time.... (Johnson) didn't get gay at all with Jeffries in the beginning, and it was always the white man who clinched, but Johnson was very careful, and he backed away and took no chances, and was good-natured with it all. \u2026 The best man won, and I was one of the first to congratulate him, and also one of the first to extend my heartfelt sympathy to the beaten man.<ref>John L. Sullivan, cited in: Christopher James Shelton, [http://www.ringsideboxingshow.com/SheltonBLOGJohnsonJeffries.html \"'Fight of the Century' Johnson vs. Jeffries, the 100th anniversary\"], Ringside Boxing Show</ref>}}\n\n==Later years and death==\nIn his later years, Jeffries trained boxers and worked as a fight promoter. He promoted many fights out of a structure known as \"Jeffries Barn\", which was located on his alfalfa ranch at the southwest corner of Victory Boulevard and Buena Vista, Burbank, California. (His ranch house was on the southeast corner until the early 1960s.) Jeffries Barn is now part of [[Knott's Berry Farm]], a [[Southern California]] amusement park. \n\nSeven years after suffering a stroke, Jeffries died on March 3, 1953, in bed at his home with his niece Lillian Bull. Bull had been living with Jeffries as his housekeeper and he had instructed her to call a doctor. Jeffries died before the doctor arrived. The doctor, William M. Nethery, attributed his death to a [[heart attack]] caused by [[coronary thrombosis]].<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19530304&id=7DBdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EVsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4372,1685873&hl=en</ref> His body was interred in the [[Inglewood Park Cemetery]] in [[Inglewood, California]].\n\n==Legacy==\nToday, the legacy of Jeffries is widely forgotten. However, he was once considered one of the greatest Heavyweight Champions of all time by many fellow boxers and boxing experts:<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MtOjXb3EsW4|title=How Does Jim Jeffries Rank?|date=2 October 2006|work=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eI8mVLPbvLw|title=How Good Was Jim Jeffries?|date=3 October 2006|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jack Root]], [[Willie Ritchie]] and [[Tommy Burns (boxer)|Tommy Burns]], former Light Heavyweight, Lightweight and Heavyweight Champions, respectively, rated Jeffries as the greatest heavyweight.\n*[[James J. Corbett]] said of Jeffries, \"The thing the always impressed me was the speed the youngster had, and he weighed two-hundred-twenty-five pounds. I hold that Jeffries was the greatest Heavyweight Champion of them all.\"\n\n*[[Sam Langford]], the great fighter who fought from lightweight to heavyweight, advertised to fight any man in the world, except Jim Jeffries.\n\n*[[Tom Sharkey]], heavyweight top contender, thought that Jeffries would have beaten [[Jack Dempsey]] and [[Joe Louis]] on the same night. He said Jeffries was strong like a bull and quick on his feet like a cat. Sharkey called Jeffries the greatest fighter of all time.\n\n*[[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]], the only man to beat Jeffries, stated in an interview with Ring Magazine that he thought Jeffries was the greatest. In another interview, Johnson said Jeffries would beat both Jack Dempsey and Joe Louis.  However, in turn, Jeffries said after their bout: \"I could never have whipped Johnson at my best. I couldn't have hit him. No, I couldn't have reached him in 1,000 years.\" <ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web|title=Jack Johnson Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/jack-johnson-9355980|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n \n*Jack Dempsey, the great Heavyweight Champion, once said: \"Jim Jeffries was a tough gun. If we could have gotten in the ring together, each at our best... I probably would have had my chin knocked off.\"\n\n*[[William A. Brady|William Brady]], who managed both Jim Jeffries and Jim Corbett, remarked about Jeffries: \"There was never a man fitted anatomically, physically, and temperamentally for the role of World's Heavyweight Champion.\"\n\n*[[Nat Fleischer]], founder of Ring Magazine and The Ring Record book, described Jeffries: \"One of the most formidable fighting machines the prize ring ever produced.\"\n\n*[[Dan Morgan]], fight manager for forty years, who saw them all, rated Jeffries as the all-time best. Morgan called Jeffries a \"Champion of Champions.\"\n\n*[[Tex Rickard]], famed sportsman and promoter, held the view: \"Big Jim will always live in my memory as the greatest heavyweight boxer of his time. While he reigned supreme, he gave all a chance. He did not know the meaning of the word fear.\"\n\n*W. W. Naughton, sports writer of the day, records: \"To sum up his qualities of ringsmanship, it may be said he is fairly talented in every branch of self-defense. He boxes cleverly, defends himself well, and strikes a hard blow. But back of all these are the qualities which have made him a champion, magnificent strength and wonderful endurance.\"\n\n*Dewitt Van Court, boxing instructor and athletic director of the [[Los Angeles]] Athletic Club wrote: \"I was with James J. Jeffries when he first started to box. I was with him when he won the Championship. I was with him when he lost it. Besides being the greatest Heavyweight Champion that ever lived, he is today and has been all his life, a man among men, a true friend with a heart as big as his body.\"\n\nThe city of Burbank embedded a small bronze plaque in the sidewalk at the site where James Jeffries died. The plaque was located on the southeast side of Buena Vista ~150 yards south of Victory Boulevard, before being stored at Burbank City Hall, and now is located at the Gordon R. Howard Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/burbank-leader/entertainment/tn-blr-me-community-20180604-story.html|title=Community: New exhibit piece at Burbank museum is a real knockout|last=Rudolph|first=Joyce|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nJames J. Jeffries was elected to the [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]] in 1990.\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=2\n|nc=2\n|ko-wins=16\n|ko-losses=1\n|dec-wins=3\n|dec-losses=0\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=0\n}}\n{{clear}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|24\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|19\u20131\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]\n|TKO\n|15 (45), {{small|2:20}}\n|4 July 1910\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Reno, Nevada]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Lost lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|23\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|19\u20130\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|CAN}} Jack Munroe\n|TKO\n|2 (20), {{small|0:45}}\n|26 Aug 1904\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Mechanic's Pavilion, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|22\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|18\u20130\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[James J. Corbett]]\n|TKO\n|10 (20)\n|14 Aug 1903\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Mechanic's Pavilion, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|21\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|17\u20130\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Bob Fitzsimmons]]\n|KO\n|8 (20)\n|25 Jul 1902\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|San Francisco Athletic Club, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|20\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|16\u20130\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Gus Ruhlin\n|RTD\n|6 (20)\n|15 Nov 1901\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Mechanic's Pavilion, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|19\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|15\u20130\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Joe Kennedy\n|KO\n|2 (4), {{small|2:00}}\n|24 Sep 1901\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Reliance Athletic Club]], [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|18\n|style=\"background:#DDD\"|{{abbr|NC|No contest}}\n|14\u20130\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Hank Griffin\n|NC\n|4\n|17 Sep 1901\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Hazard's Pavilion, Los Angeles, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|17\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|14\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[James J. Corbett]]\n|KO\n|23 (25), {{small|2:11}}\n|11 May 1900\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Seaside Athletic Club, [[Coney Island]], New York, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|16\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|13\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} John Finnegan\n|KO\n|1 (10), {{small|0:55}}\n|6 Apr 1900\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Cadillac Athletic Club, [[Detroit, Michigan]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|15\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|12\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Tom Sharkey]]\n|PTS\n|25\n|3 Nov 1899\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Coney Island Athletic Club, Brooklyn, New York, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained lineal heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|14\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|11\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Bob Fitzsimmons]]\n|KO\n|11 (20), {{small|1:32}}\n|9 Jun 1899\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Coney Island Athletic Club, [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won [[Lineal championship|lineal heavyweight title]]}}\n|-\n|13\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|10\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bob Armstrong (boxer)|Bob Armstrong]]\n|PTS\n|10\n|5 Aug 1898\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Lenox Athletic Club, [[New York City, New York]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|12\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|9\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Tom Sharkey]]\n|PTS\n|20\n|6 May 1898\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Mechanic's Pavilion, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|11\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|8\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Mexican Pete Everett\n|TKO\n|3 (20), {{small|1:30}}\n|22 Apr 1898\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Olympic Athletic Club, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|10\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|7\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter Jackson (boxer)|Peter Jackson]]\n|TKO\n|3 (20)\n|22 Mar 1898\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Woodward's Gardens|Woodward's Pavilion]], San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|9\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|6\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|AUS}} Joe Goddard\n|TKO\n|4 (15)\n|28 Feb 1898\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Hazard's Pavilion, Los Angeles, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|8\n|{{draw}}Draw\n|5\u20130\u20132 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Choynski]]\n|PTS\n|20\n|30 Nov 1897\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|National Athletic Club, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|7\n|style=\"background:#DDD\"|{{abbr|NC|No contest}}\n|5\u20130\u20131 {{small|(1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Dan Long\n|{{abbr|NC|No contest}}\n|6\n|25 Aug 1897\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Hazard's Pavilion]], [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|6\n|{{draw}}Draw\n|5\u20130\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Gus Ruhlin\n|{{abbr|PTS|Points decision}}\n|20\n|16 Jul 1897\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[San Francisco Mechanics' Institute|Mechanic's Pavilion]], San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|5\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|5\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Henry Baker\n|TKO\n|9 (20)\n|18 May 1897\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Olympic Club|Olympic Athletic Club]], San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|4\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|4\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Theodore Van Buskirk\n|KO\n|2 (15), {{small|2:00}}\n|9 Apr 1897\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|National Athletic Club, San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|3\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|3\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Hank Griffin\n|KO\n|14\n|1 Dec 1896\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Oakland Tribune]], San Francisco, California, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Exact date is uncertain}}\n|-\n|2\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|2\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Dan Long\n|{{abbr|TKO|Technical knockout}}\n|2 (10)\n|2 Jul 1896\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Occidental Athletic Club, [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], California, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|1\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|1\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Hank Lorraine\n|{{abbr|KO|Knockout}}\n|2 (4)\n|29 Oct 1895\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Los Angeles Athletic Club]], [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|}\n\n==Selected filmography==\n*''[[Kid Speed]]'' (1924)\n*''[[One Round Hogan]]'' (1927)\n*''[[Beau Broadway]]'' (1928)\n*''[[Rain or Shine (film)|Rain or Shine]]'' (1930)\n*''[[The Fighting Gentleman]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[Midnight Patrol (1932 film)|Midnight Patrol]]'' (1932)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of heavyweight boxing champions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/jeffrx.htm James J. Jeffries - CBZ Profile]\n*{{boxrec|id=009022}}\n*{{IMDb name|0420375}}\n*[http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/oldtimer/jeffries.html Boxing Hall of Fame]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160227023056/http://www.lordheath.com/index.php?p=1_804_James-J-Jeffries brieg article on James J. Jeffries as a Laurel & Hardy player]\n*{{Find a Grave|3548}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Bob Fitzsimmons]] |\n  title= World Heavyweight Champion |\n  years= June 9, 1899\u2013May 13, 1905<br />Vacated |\n  after= [[Marvin Hart]]<br /><small>Filled vacancy</small> \n}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box | title=Most opponents beaten<br />for the world heavyweight championship<br />{{small|6}} | before=[[James J. Corbett]] | after=[[Tommy Burns (boxer)|Tommy Burns]] | years=6 April 1900\u20132 December 1907 }}\n{{succession box | title=Most wins in<br />world heavyweight championship fights<br />{{small|8}} | before=[[James J. Corbett]] | after=[[Tommy Burns (boxer)|Tommy Burns]] | years=6 April 1900\u201317 March 1908 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeffries, James J.}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Boxers from California]]\n[[Category:American boilermakers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Inglewood Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:World heavyweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World boxing champions]]\n[[Category:International Boxing Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n[[Category:People from Fairfield County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Deaths from coronary thrombosis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{refimprove|date = February 2019}}\n{{other people|James Jeffries}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n|name=James J. Jeffries\n|image=James J Jeffries.jpg\n|realname=James Jackson Jeffries\n|nickname=[[Boilermaker|The Boilermaker]]<br>Big Jeff<br>Big Jim<br>Jim\n|weight=[[Heavyweight]]\n|height=6 ft 1+1/2 in\n|reach=76+1/2 in\n|nationality=United States\n|birth_date={{birth date|1875|04|15|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Carroll, Ohio]], [[United States|US]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1953|03|03|1875|04|15|mf=y}}\n|death_place=[[Burbank, California]], [[United States|US]]\n|style=[[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n|total=24\n|wins=19\n|KO=16\n|losses=1\n|draws=2\n|no contests=2\n}}\n'''James Jackson''' \"'''Jim'''\" '''Jeffries''' (April 15, 1875 \u2013 March 3, 1953) was an [[Americans|American]] professional [[Boxing|boxer]] and World Heavyweight Champion.\n\nHe was known for his enormous strength and stamina. Using a technique taught to him by his trainer, former [[Welterweight]] and [[Middleweight]] Champion [[Tommy Ryan]], Jeffries fought out of a crouch with his left arm extended forward. He was able to absorb tremendous punishment while wearing his opponents down. A natural left-hander, he possessed one-punch knockout power in his left hook, and brawled his way to the top of the rankings. He is perhaps most famous for being United States \"Great White Hope\", since the nation expected him to come out of his retirement to beat the African-American boxer [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]], who was at the time the Heavyweight Champion.<ref>https://search.alexanderstreet.com/preview/work/bibliographic_entity%7Cvideo_work%7C1789067?ssotoken=anonymous</ref>\n\nJeffries stood {{convert|6|ft|1+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}} tall and weighed {{convert|225|lb}} in his prime. He could run {{convert|100|yd|m}} in just over ten seconds, and could high jump over {{convert|6|ft|cm}}.\n\n==Early life==\nJeffries moved with his family from their Ohio farm to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] at age seven.<ref>http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/oldtimer/jeffries.html</ref> He worked for a while as a [[boilermaker]] before going into boxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=1409&more=1|title=WardDawsonSDown2|author=ES Boxing|work=Boxing News 24/7}}</ref> In later life, \"The Boilermaker\" was one of his professional nicknames.\n\n==Career==\nAs a powerfully built and athletic teenager, Jeffries boxed as an amateur until age 20, when he started fighting professionally.\n\nIn his third fight, Jeffries knocked out the highly regarded boxer [[Hank Griffin (boxer)|Hank Griffin]] in the fourteenth round. [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]] would subsequently fight Griffin on three separate occasions.\n\nJeffries fought the top heavyweight contender, Gus Ruhlin, to a draw. Ruhlin was knocked down with a brutal punch at the end of the final round and was saved by the bell from being counted out. The decision was met with unfavorable reactions from the audience, many of whom felt Jeffries won.\n\nOn his way to the title in 1898, Jeffries knocked out [[Peter Jackson (boxer)|Peter Jackson]], the great boxer whom [[John L. Sullivan]] had refused to fight, in three rounds. This had been only the second defeat in Jackson's entire career; his first loss was from a four-round fight over thirteen years earlier around the beginning of his career. Jackson retired shortly afterward.\n\nJeffries defeated the formidable Mexican Pete Everett by knockout in only the third round on April 22, 1898.\n\nHis next fight was against the Irishman [[Tom Sharkey]]. The fight went the full twenty rounds and Sharkey was knocked down in the eleventh round. Jeffries won the decision.\n\nAfter defeating the big, fast-moving, sharp-jabbing [[Bob Armstrong (boxer)|Bob Armstrong]], Jeffries had earned the right to challenge for the World Heavyweight Championship.\n\nOn June 9, 1899 in [[Brooklyn, New York]] he defeated [[Bob Fitzsimmons]] by KO in the eleventh round to win the [[Heavyweight]] Championship of the World. That August, he embarked on a tour of [[Europe]], putting on exhibition fights for the fans. Jeffries was involved in several motion pictures recreating portions of his championship fights. Filmed portions of his other bouts and of some of his exhibition matches survive to this day.\n\n===World Heavyweight Champion===\nIn his first title defense, he won a twenty-five-round decision in a rematch over Tom Sharkey.\n\nJeffries set the record for the quickest KO in a Heavyweight title fight ever, which was 55 seconds against Jack Finnegan in his second title defense.\n\nHis next defense was against the former [[Heavyweight]] Champion and legendary technician, [[James J. Corbett]]. Corbett had put up a perfect defense and could have arguably won had the fight gone the distance. However, Corbett was knocked out cold from a left to the jaw in the twenty-third round of the scheduled twenty-five round fight.\n\nJeffries later got the chance to avenge his controversial draw with Gus Ruhlin when he defended his title against him on November 15, 1901. Claims that Ruhlin quit during the fifth round are incorrect. All of the local next-day San Francisco sources agree that Ruhlin's manager, Billy Madden, threw in the towel to retire Gus during the one-minute interval between the fifth and sixth rounds.\n\nAn example of Jeffries' ability to absorb punishment and recover from a severe battering to win a bout came in his rematch for the title with Fitzsimmons, who is regarded as one of the hardest punchers in boxing history. The rematch with Jeffries occurred on July 25, 1902 in [[San Francisco]]. To train for the bout Jeffries' daily training included a {{convert|14|mi|km|sing=on}} run, 2 hours of skipping rope, medicine ball training, 20 minutes sparring on the heavy bag, and at least 12 rounds of sparring in the ring. He also trained in wrestling.\n\nFor nearly eight rounds Fitzsimmons subjected Jeffries to a vicious battering. Jeffries suffered a broken nose, both his cheeks were cut to the bone, and gashes were opened over both eyes. It appeared that the fight would have to be stopped, as blood freely flowed into Jeffries' eyes. Then in the eighth round, Jeffries lashed out with a terrific right to the stomach, followed by a left hook to the jaw which knocked Fitzsimmons unconscious.\n\nJeffries and Corbett met one last time in the ring on August 14, 1903. This time Jeffries was in total control for all ten rounds of the scheduled twenty round bout. Tommy Ryan, Corbett's chief second, threw a large palm-leaf fan into the ring to alert Referee Graney that he should stop the fight.\n\nJeffries had his seventh and final title defense against Canadian Jack Munroe, whom he stopped in only two rounds.\n\nJeffries broke the ribs of three opponents in title fights: [[James J. Corbett|Jim Corbett]], Gus Ruhlin and [[Tom Sharkey]]. Jeffries retired undefeated in May 1905. He served as a referee for the next few years, including the bout in which [[Marvin Hart]] defeated [[Jack Root]] to stake a claim at Jeffries' vacated title. Jeffries had never been knocked down in his prime.\n\nJeffries had likely fought many more bouts than twenty-two at this time. Many of his fights were lost in history. Jeffries, however, had never been defeated before his original retirement.\n\n===Comeback: \"The Fight of the Century\"===\n[[File:Johnson jeff.jpg|left|thumb|200px|James Jeffries during his fight with [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]]]\nOver five years after retiring, Jeffries made a comeback on July 4, 1910 at [[Reno, Nevada]] in a match against champion [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]], who had won the [[Heavyweight]] Championship in 1908 by defeating Canadian champion [[Tommy Burns (boxer)|Tommy Burns]] at [[Rushcutters Bay, New South Wales|Rushcutters Bay]] in Australia. Burns was the first heavyweight champion to fight African-American challengers.\n\nThe media put pressure onto Jeffries and promoters dangled wealth in front of him to take the fight. He finally acquiesced, saying \"I am going into this fight for the sole purpose of proving that a white man is better than a negro.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Zirin |first=Dave|year=2008 |title=\nPeople's History of Sports in the United States: 250 Years of Politics, Protest, People, and Play|publisher=The New Press|page=42|ISBN=1595581006}}</ref> In addition to a guaranteed purse of $40,000 (equivalent to approximately ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|40000|1910|r=0}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}), to woo the ex-champ back into the ring, promoter [[Tex Rickard]] had signed him to a $75,000 personal contract.\n\nAfter a six-year lay-off, the 35-year-old Jeffries was out of shape and had lost most of his muscle. Jeffries weighed over 330 pounds (150&nbsp;kg), while Johnson was in superb physical condition. The ex-champ had to lose 110 pounds to get down to his fighting weight of 226, a Herculean task in the time he had before the fight. Previous Heavyweight Champion [[John L. Sullivan]] (an ethnic Irish American who refused to fight African-American contenders) remarked during an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' that Jeffries' personal doctor was so amazed at Johnson's physical condition that he felt Jeffries could win only if Johnson had a lack of skill on the day. While the media instigated racist remarks about winning the title for whites, Jeffries' final words before the fight were, \"It is my intention to go right after my opponent and knock him out as soon as possible.\" His wife also commented, \"I'm not interested in prizefighting but I am interested in my husband's welfare, I do hope this will be his last fight.\"<ref>[http://www.aolnews.com/2010/07/04/jack-johnson-jim-jeffries-highlighted-u-s-racial-divide/ \"Jack Johnson-Jim Jeffries Fight Highlighted the US Racial Divide\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302193813/http://www.aolnews.com/2010/07/04/jack-johnson-jim-jeffries-highlighted-u-s-racial-divide/ |date=2012-03-02 }}, 4 July 2010, AOL News</ref>\n\n{{YouTube|L1y76L2P-IQ|Motion picture footage}} of Jeffries on the morning of the fight depicts a relaxed man playing with his dog. Ringside seats that had been priced at $50 were being scalped at $125 each (equivalent to approximately ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|125|1910|r=0}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}). More than 1,000 spectators who were unable to get seats in the sold-out arena climbed over the walls to enter.\n\nBefore the fight, which was scheduled for 45 three-minute rounds, famous boxers who had traveled to Reno to witness the contest were introduced to the crowd, including [[Sam Langford]], a black boxer who was unable to secure a title fight, even from Jack Johnson. The greatest applause went to [[Jake Kilrain]], who had battled John L. Sullivan back in the bare-knuckle days.\n\nAt three minutes to one P.M., Johnson entered the ring (his contract provided that he would always be first to enter the ring, to satisfy a superstition of his). The thermometer read 110\u00b0 Fahrenheit, which meant the match would be even more brutal due to heat. Jeffries soon joined Johnson in the ring. Rickard served as referee. (Johnson and Jeffries could not agree on a referee, and Rickard's publicity-minded offers to President [[William Howard Taft]] and writer [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] to serve as referee were declined. Rickard took the position although he had never refereed a prize fight before.)\n\nIn the first three rounds, the boxers sparred to feel each other out. Johnson, having read that no one could tie Jeffries up on the inside due to his power, told the press that not only would he do so, but that he planned to neutralize Jeffries' power by twisting his arms behind him. Toward the end of the fourth round, he did just that, pinning Jeffries' arms in back of him for a moment, but Jeffries broke the clinch. Johnson landed a solid overhand right to Jeffries' head just before the bell.\n\nJohnson began dominating the fight in rounds five through twelve, as his opponent faded in the heat and from Johnson's onslaught. The heat began to get to Johnson, too, by round 13, but he was still the stronger and younger man in the ring. Toward the end of that round, he delivered a right and a right uppercut to Jeffries' head that took their toll. In the next round, Jeffries eluded Johnson, who stalked him all over the ring.\n\nIn round 15, Johnson went after Jeffries and caught him against the ropes with a right upper-cut, followed by three left uppercuts that sent the ex-champ to the canvas for the first time in his career. He could no longer put up a defense and, as Jeffries got up, Johnson hit him with a left hook that sent him to the canvas and through the ropes, putting his torso outside the ring. Helped to his feet by one of his seconds and a fan, as soon as Jeffries was back in the ring he was rushed by Johnson, who knocked him down again with a right to the head. As Rickard moved in to separate the fighters, Jeffries got up, but his manager had entered the ring to stop the fight and save his fighter from being knocked out. Johnson retained the title by a [[technical knockout]].\n\nJohnson later remarked that he knew the fight was over in the 4th round when he landed an uppercut to Jeffries' face and saw the look in his eyes. \"I knew what that look meant,\" he said. \"The old ship was sinking.\" [[John L. Sullivan]] commented for ''[[The New York Times]]'' after the fight that Johnson won deservedly, fairly, and convincingly:\n\n{{quote|The fight of the century is over and a black man is the undisputed champion of the world. It was a poor fight as fights go, this less than 15-round affair between James J. Jeffries and Jack Johnson. Scarcely has there ever been a championship contest that was so one-sided. All of Jeffries much-vaunted condition amounted to nothing. He wasn't in it from the first bell tap to the last \u2026. The negro had few friends, but there was little demonstration against him. (Spectators) could not help but admire Johnson because he is the type of prizefighter that is admired by sportsmen. He played fairly at all times and fought fairly. \u2026 What a crafty, powerful, cunning left hand (Johnson) has. He is one of the craftiest, cunningest boxers that ever stepped into the ring. \u2026 They both fought closely all during the 15 rounds. It was just the sort of fight that Jeffries wanted. There was no running or ducking like Corbett did with me in New Orleans (1892). Jeffries did not miss so many blows, because he hardly started any. Johnson was on top of him all the time.... (Johnson) didn't get gay at all with Jeffries in the beginning, and it was always the white man who clinched, but Johnson was very careful, and he backed away and took no chances, and was good-natured with it all. \u2026 The best man won, and I was one of the first to congratulate him, and also one of the first to extend my heartfelt sympathy to the beaten man.<ref>John L. Sullivan, cited in: Christopher James Shelton, [http://www.ringsideboxingshow.com/SheltonBLOGJohnsonJeffries.html \"'Fight of the Century' Johnson vs. Jeffries, the 100th anniversary\"], Ringside Boxing Show</ref>}}\n\n==Later years and death==\nIn his later years, Jeffries trained boxers and worked as a fight promoter. He promoted many fights out of a structure known as \"Jeffries Barn\", which was located on his alfalfa ranch at the southwest corner of Victory Boulevard and Buena Vista, Burbank, California. (His ranch house was on the southeast corner until the early 1960s.) Jeffries Barn is now part of [[Knott's Berry Farm]], a [[Southern California]] amusement park. \n\nSeven years after suffering a stroke, Jeffries died on March 3, 1953, in bed at his home with his neice Lillian Bull. Bull had been living with Jeffries as his housekeeper and he had instructed her to call a doctor. Jeffries died before the doctor arrived. The doctor, William M. Nethery, attributed his death to a [[heart attack]] caused by [[coronary thrombosis]].<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19530304&id=7DBdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EVsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4372,1685873&hl=en</ref> His body was interred in the [[Inglewood Park Cemetery]] in [[Inglewood, California]].\n\n==Legacy==\nToday, the legacy of Jeffries is widely forgotten. However, he was once considered one of the greatest Heavyweight Champions of all time by many fellow boxers and boxing experts:<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MtOjXb3EsW4|title=How Does Jim Jeffries Rank?|date=2 October 2006|work=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eI8mVLPbvLw|title=How Good Was Jim Jeffries?|date=3 October 2006|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jack Root]], [[Willie Ritchie]] and [[Tommy Burns (boxer)|Tommy Burns]], former Light Heavyweight, Lightweight and Heavyweight Champions, respectively, rated Jeffries as the greatest heavyweight.\n*[[James J. Corbett]] said of Jeffries, \"The thing the always impressed me was the speed the youngster had, and he weighed two-hundred-twenty-five pounds. I hold that Jeffries was the greatest Heavyweight Champion of them all.\"\n\n*[[Sam Langford]], the great fighter who fought from lightweight to heavyweight, advertised to fight any man in the world, except Jim Jeffries.\n\n*[[Tom Sharkey]], heavyweight top contender, thought that Jeffries would have beaten [[Jack Dempsey]] and [[Joe Louis]] on the same night. He said Jeffries was strong like a bull and quick on his feet like a cat. Sharkey called Jeffries the greatest fighter of all time.\n\n*[[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]], the only man to beat Jeffries, stated in an interview with Ring Magazine that he thought Jeffries was the greatest. In another interview, Johnson said Jeffries would beat both Jack Dempsey and Joe Louis.  However, in turn, Jeffries said after their bout: \"I could never have whipped Johnson at my best. I couldn't have hit him. No, I couldn't have reached him in 1,000 years.\" <ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web|title=Jack Johnson Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/jack-johnson-9355980|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n \n*Jack Dempsey, the great Heavyweight Champion, once said: \"Jim Jeffries was a tough gun. If we could have gotten in the ring together, each at our best... I probably would have had my chin knocked off.\"\n\n*[[William A. Brady|William Brady]], who managed both Jim Jeffries and Jim Corbett, remarked about Jeffries: \"There was never a man fitted anatomically, physically, and temperamentally for the role of World's Heavyweight Champion.\"\n\n*[[Nat Fleischer]], founder of Ring Magazine and The Ring Record book, described Jeffries: \"One of the most formidable fighting machines the prize ring ever produced.\"\n\n*[[Dan Morgan]], fight manager for forty years, who saw them all, rated Jeffries as the all-time best. Morgan called Jeffries a \"Champion of Champions.\"\n\n*[[Tex Rickard]], famed sportsman and promoter, held the view: \"Big Jim will always live in my memory as the greatest heavyweight boxer of his time. While he reigned supreme, he gave all a chance. He did not know the meaning of the word fear.\"\n\n*W. W. Naughton, sports writer of the day, records: \"To sum up his qualities of ringsmanship, it may be said he is fairly talented in every branch of self-defense. He boxes cleverly, defends himself well, and strikes a hard blow. But back of all these are the qualities which have made him a champion, magnificent strength and wonderful endurance.\"\n\n*Dewitt Van Court, boxing instructor and athletic director of the [[Los Angeles]] Athletic Club wrote: \"I was with James J. Jeffries when he first started to box. I was with him when he won the Championship. I was with him when he lost it. Besides being the greatest Heavyweight Champion that ever lived, he is today and has been all his life, a man among men, a true friend with a heart as big as his body.\"\n\nThe city of Burbank embedded a small bronze plaque in the sidewalk at the site where James Jeffries died. The plaque was located on the southeast side of Buena Vista ~150 yards south of Victory Boulevard, before being stored at Burbank City Hall, and now is located at the Gordon R. Howard Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/burbank-leader/entertainment/tn-blr-me-community-20180604-story.html|title=Community: New exhibit piece at Burbank museum is a real knockout|last=Rudolph|first=Joyce|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nJames J. Jeffries was elected to the [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]] in 1990.\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=2\n|nc=2\n|ko-wins=16\n|ko-losses=1\n|dec-wins=3\n|dec-losses=0\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=0\n}}\n{{clear}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|24\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|19\u20131\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]\n|TKO\n|15 (45), {{small|2:20}}\n|4 July 1910\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Reno, Nevada]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Lost l