{"title_page": "Lorne Mendell", "text_new": "{{short description|Professor of neuorbiology}}\n'''Lorne Mendell''' is a [[Neurobiology|neurobiologist]] currently employed as a distinguished professor in the department of neurobiology and behavior at [[Stony Brook University]] in [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\":0\" /> His research focuses primarily on [[neurotrophin]]s in neonatal and adult mammals, and on the neuroplasticity of the mammalian spinal cord. Mendell's research interests lie in other areas including [[pain]], nerve wind-up, and specifically the neurotrophin, [[NT-3]]. His research has contributed findings to the growing pool of knowledge of [[axon]]al development and regeneration of immature and mature neurons. Mendell has been a part of the search for novel treatments for [[spinal cord]] injuries, and Mendell continues to study neurotrophins to determine their effects on neuronal plasticity. Mendell served a term as the President for the Society of Neuroscience during the years 1997-1998.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nLorne Mendell graduated from [[McGill University]] in 1961 with a bachelor of science in both [[mathematics]] and [[physics]]. He went on to earn his Ph.D. from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (M.I.T.) in 1965. Shortly after earning his Ph.D., Mendell became a faculty member at [[Duke University Medical Center]] in 1968. He remained at Duke until 1980 when he joined the faculty at Stony Brook University. Since then, Mendell has held numerous positions in a number of associations and organizations. He has also received many honors and awards throughout his career as a neurobiologist.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu/neurobiology/faculty/Mendell|title=Lorne Mendell {{!}} Renaissance School of Medicine at Stony Brook University|website=renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLorne Mendell is married to Nancy Mendell, a professor emerita in the department of applied mathematics and statistics at Stony Brook University. Together they have a daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.galvnews.com/announcements/weddings/article_ab71a603-7254-5179-b00e-cdf16005c16c.html|title=Mendell-Hodgson|website=The Daily News|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Research focus ===\n\nMendell's research within [[neurotrophin]]s has focused specifically on [[nerve growth factor]]s (NGF) and their role that they play within inflammatory pain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dray|first=A|date=August 1995|title=Inflammatory mediators of pain|journal=British Journal of Anaesthesia|volume=75|issue=2|pages=125\u2013131|doi=10.1093/bja/75.2.125|issn=0007-0912}}</ref> Within this, there was also a focus in [[brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) and their sensitizing effect on specific [[synaptic transmission]] between [[nociceptor]]s and their target.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crozier|first=Robert A.|last2=Bi|first2=Caixia|last3=Han|first3=Yu R.|last4=Plummer|first4=Mark R.|date=2008-12-01|title=BDNF Modulation of NMDA Receptors Is Activity Dependent|url=https://journals.physiology.org/doi/full/10.1152/jn.90418.2008|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=100|issue=6|pages=3264\u20133274|doi=10.1152/jn.90418.2008|issn=0022-3077|pmc=2604850|pmid=18842955}}</ref> In his recent labs, he has been studying the contributions of a third [[Neurotrophin-3|neurotrophin]] (NT-3) and what the effects are when the [[synapse]] that is involved in [[transmission]] between [[stretch receptor]]s and [[motor neuron]]s is altered.\n\nMendell's research on [[neuronal plasticity]] is specifically focused on the [[Spinal cord|mammalian spinal cord]]. He has combined some of his research from NT-3 to help show how neurotrophins can help alter the function of both damaged and undamaged neurons.\n\nMuch of the work Mendell has done with both neurotrophin and neuronal plasticity has some overlap into the realm of [[pain]], and what their roles are in both reducing and relieving pain. For example, Mendell has conducted research which has shown the relationship between [[nerve growth factor]]s (a type of neurotrophin) and inflammatory pain.\n\nMendell discovered the property of [[windup pain]] in the [[spinal cord]]. Windup is the property of [[Group C nerve fiber|C-fibres]] in the [[Peripheral nervous system|peripheral nerves]] of the spinal cord that when stimulated at repetitious low frequencies there will be a gradual accumulation in the amplitude of response.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolf|first=Clifford J.|date=August 1996|title=Windup and central sensitization are not equivalent|url=https://journals.lww.com/pain/Citation/1996/08000/Windup_and_central_sensitization_are_not.1.aspx|journal=PAIN|volume=66|issue=2|pages=105\u2013108|issn=0304-3959}}</ref>\n\nMendell has been interested in the role neurotrophins play in nervous plasticity since at least the mid 1990s. At the time, neurotrophins were understood to be significant factors in neuronal development and [[Differentiation (biology)|differentiation]] in the [[Central nervous system|central]] and [[peripheral nervous system]], however; scientists were still exploring the specific functions of individual neurotrophins. Subsequent findings suggested that neurotrophins have effects on both damaged and undamaged neurons. As such, neurotrophins are a major facet of [[spinal cord injury]] research. Mendell's research on neurotrophins has evolved synchronously with the understanding of neurotrophins. In more recent times, Mendell\u2019s research has been focused partly on spinal cord injury and the use of neurotophins as a possible treatment.  \t\n\n[[Hyperalgesia]], increase of sensitivity to a stimulus, was found by Mendell to be influenced by the introduction of [[nerve growth factor]], NGF. It functions by interactions with sensory [[Nociceptor|nociceptive]] neurons. Mendell was able to investigate how [[rodent]]s and [[mammal]]s sensitivity to thermal and mechanical stimulus was increased through exposure to NGF.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molliver|first=D. C|last2=Wright|first2=D. E|last3=Leitner|first3=M. L|last4=Parsadanian|first4=A. Sh|last5=Doster|first5=K|last6=Wen|first6=D|last7=Yan|first7=Q|last8=Snider|first8=W. D|date=1997-10-01|title=IB4-Binding DRG Neurons Switch from NGF to GDNF Dependence in Early Postnatal Life|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627300809666|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=19|issue=4|pages=849\u2013861|doi=10.1016/S0896-6273(00)80966-6|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> NGF was shown by Mendell to also play a role in the development of young mammals. Mature animals, he showed, that NGF had a possible role in the linkage of [[hyperalgesia]] and [[inflammation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.lww.com/anesthesia-analgesia/Fulltext/2007/09000/Pathophysiology_of_Peripheral_Neuropathic_Pain_.44.aspx|title=Pathophysiology of Peripheral Neuropathic Pain: Immune... : Anesthesia & Analgesia|website=LWW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Major works and contributions ==\nIn 1965, Mendell's doctoral dissertation was published in the academic journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''. The dissertation was about\u00a0how [[Group C nerve fiber|C fibres]] in the dorsal horn affect the A fibres. He concluded that his evidence did not support the idea that the firing of C fibres had an effect on the presynaptic hyperpolarization of the A fibres of the cats that were experimented on.\n\nIn April 2016, Mendell helped to publish a paper<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harrison|first=Benjamin J.|last2=Venkat|first2=Gayathri|last3=Lamb|first3=James L.|last4=Hutson|first4=Tom H.|last5=Drury|first5=Cassa|last6=Rau|first6=Kristofer K.|last7=Bunge|first7=Mary Barlett|last8=Mendell|first8=Lorne M.|last9=Gage|first9=Fred H.|last10=Johnson|first10=Richard D.|last11=Hill|first11=Caitlin E.|date=2016-04-13|title=The Adaptor Protein CD2AP Is a Coordinator of Neurotrophin Signaling-Mediated Axon Arbor Plasticity|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/36/15/4259|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=36|issue=15|pages=4259\u20134275|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2423-15.2016|issn=0270-6474|pmid=27076424}}</ref> that focused on the relationship between a protein called [[CD2AP]] and the plasticity of [[neuron]]s. It is known that the growth of an [[axon]] of a neuron helps with both the adaptive and maladaptive [[Neuroplasticity|plasticity]] within the [[nervous system]]. Therefore, if an axon becomes injured, or cannot function to its best ability, the consequences can be in the form of [[Neurological disorder|neurologic disease]]. The protein CD2AP in this study was looked at in depth, which is responsible for coordinating axon outgrowth. Mendell and his team were able to observe that CD2AP is amplified within [[dorsal root ganglion]]s (DRGs) during axonal sprouting, but decreases in quantity during axonal [[Regeneration (biology)|regeneration]]. Based on these findings, it is still undetermined what the exact relationship between the control of the regeneration of previously damaged axons and the additional development of non-damaged axons is.\n\nIn another one of his studies,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mantyh|first=Patrick W.|last2=Koltzenburg|first2=Martin|last3=Mendell|first3=Lorne M.|last4=Tive|first4=Leslie|last5=Shelton|first5=David L.|date=2011-07-01|title=Antagonism of Nerve Growth Factor-TrkA Signaling and the Relief of Pain|url=https://anesthesiology.pubs.asahq.org/article.aspx?articleid=1933906|journal=Anesthesiology: The Journal of the American Society of Anesthesiologists|language=en|volume=115|issue=1|pages=189\u2013204|doi=10.1097/ALN.0b013e31821b1ac5|issn=0003-3022}}</ref> conducted in July 2011, Mendell et al. looked at the mechanisms involved in the relationship between [[Nerve growth factor|neuronal growth factors]] (NGF), which is a [[neurotrophin]], and pain. It is known that specific mutations in NGF or [[Tropomyosin receptor kinase A|TrkA]] genes can lead to a decrease in the sensitivity to [[pain]]. However, the NGF-TrkA axis, on the other hand, can facilitate the development of many different types of long-term acute and [[chronic pain]]. With this, this study was able to conclude that one has to look at how many NGF-responsive (meaning how many are TrkA-positive) [[nociceptor]]s are actually connected to the tissue where the pain is coming from. This is an important relationship because the amount of [[Nerve|innervation]] widely varies between different types of tissue. Then, once this has been examined, one can more effectively choose which chronic pain state to target. Therefore, if it is able to be applied effectively, choosing therapies that rely on targeting NGF-TrkA signaling may represent a new way to treat different types of chronic pain.\n\nMendell has also put forth research<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Garc\u00eda-Al\u00edas|first=Guillermo|last2=Petrosyan|first2=Hayk A.|last3=Schnell|first3=Lisa|last4=Horner|first4=Philip J.|last5=Bowers|first5=William J.|last6=Mendell|first6=Lorne M.|last7=Fawcett|first7=James W.|last8=Arvanian|first8=Victor L.|date=2011-12-07|title=Chondroitinase ABC Combined with Neurotrophin NT-3 Secretion and NR2D Expression Promotes Axonal Plasticity and Functional Recovery in Rats with Lateral Hemisection of the Spinal Cord|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/31/49/17788|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=31|issue=49|pages=17788\u201317799|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4308-11.2011|issn=0270-6474|pmid=22159095}}</ref> about the increased possibility of promoting [[spinal cord]] repair through a combination of several different [[treatment]]s. The mechanisms involved in this are due to the additive effects when several different neurotrophins and [[protein]]s are combined, including [[Chondroitin ABC lyase|chondroitinase ABC]], [[Neurotrophin-3|NT3]], and enhanced levels of [[NR2D]]. These together allow for either the synthesis or strengthening of spinal circuits, as well as slight recovery of function for those that have been damaged.\n\n=== Positions held ===\n*Chair of the Department of Neurobiology and Behavior, [[Stony Brook University]], 1986-2006\n*''[[Journal of Neurophysiology]]'' editor-in-chief, 1983-1989\n*On the Editorial Board for the [[Journal of Neurophysiology]], current\n*On the Editorial Board for the [[The Journal of Neuroscience|Journal of Neuroscience]], 1983-1989\n*On the Council for the [[Society for Neuroscience]], 1986-1990\n*President of the Association of Neuroscience Departments and Programs, 1991-1992\n*Treasurer of the [[Society for Neuroscience]], 1996-1997\n*President of the [[Society for Neuroscience]], 1997-1998\n*[[Board of directors|Board of Directors]] for the Craig Neilsen Foundation, 2009\n*Chairman for the [[Spinal Cord Injury|Spinal Cord Injury Research Board]] of the State of New York, 2013\n*Senior Editor for [[Neuroplasticity]] for the [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] Press Research Encyclopedia in Neuroscience, 2015<ref name=\"renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu/neurobiology/honors|title=Awards and Honors {{!}} Renaissance School of Medicine at Stony Brook University|website=renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Honors and awards ===\n*Distinguished professor of Neurobiology and Behavior at [[Stony Brook University]]\n*Member of the London (UK) Pain Consortium Advisory Board, 2009-2014\n*Chosen to give the [[History of neuroscience|History of Neuroscience]] plenary lecture (\u201cThe Emergence of Contemporary Pain Neuroscience\u201d) during the Annual Meeting of the Society for Neuroscience, 2012 \n*Member of the International Science Advisory Council of Brain Canada, 2014\n*Named a fellow for the [[American Physiological Society]] Inaugural Class, 2015<ref name=\"renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mendell, Lorne}}\n[[Category:Neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University School of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Stony Brook University faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professor of neuorbiology}}\n'''Lorne Mendell''' is a [[Neurobiology|neurobiologist]] currently employed as a distinguished professor in the department of neurobiology and behavior at [[Stony Brook University]] in [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\":0\" /> His research focuses primarily on [[neurotrophin]]s in neonatal and adult mammals, and on the neuroplasticity of the mammalian spinal cord. Mendell's research interests lie in other areas including [[pain]], nerve wind-up, and specifically the neurotrophin, [[NT-3]]. His research has contributed findings to the growing pool of knowledge of [[axon]]al development and regeneration of immature and mature neurons. Mendell has been a part of the search for novel treatments for [[spinal cord]] injuries, and Mendell continues to study neurotrophins to determine their effects on neuronal plasticity. Mendell served a term as the President for the Society of Neuroscience during the years 1997-1998.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nLorne Mendell graduated from [[McGill University]] in 1961 with a bachelor of science in both [[mathematics]] and [[physics]]. He went on to earn his Ph.D. from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (M.I.T.) in 1965. Shortly after earning his Ph.D., Mendell became a faculty member at [[Duke University Medical Center]] in 1968. He remained at Duke until 1980 when he joined the faculty at Stony Brook University. Since then, Mendell has held numerous positions in a number of associations and organizations. He has also received many honors and awards throughout his career as a neurobiologist.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu/neurobiology/faculty/Mendell|title=Lorne Mendell {{!}} Renaissance School of Medicine at Stony Brook University|website=renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLorne Mendell is married to Nancy Mendell, a professor emerita in the department of applied mathematics and statistics at Stony Brook University. Together they have a daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.galvnews.com/announcements/weddings/article_ab71a603-7254-5179-b00e-cdf16005c16c.html|title=Mendell-Hodgson|website=The Daily News|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Research focus ===\n\nMendell's research within [[neurotrophin]]s has focused specifically on [[nerve growth factor]]s (NGF) and their role that they play within inflammatory pain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dray|first=A|date=August 1995|title=Inflammatory mediators of pain|journal=British Journal of Anaesthesia|volume=75|issue=2|pages=125\u2013131|doi=10.1093/bja/75.2.125|issn=0007-0912}}</ref> Within this, there was also a focus in [[brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) and their sensitizing effect on specific [[synaptic transmission]] between [[nociceptor]]s and their target.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crozier|first=Robert A.|last2=Bi|first2=Caixia|last3=Han|first3=Yu R.|last4=Plummer|first4=Mark R.|date=2008-12-01|title=BDNF Modulation of NMDA Receptors Is Activity Dependent|url=https://journals.physiology.org/doi/full/10.1152/jn.90418.2008|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=100|issue=6|pages=3264\u20133274|doi=10.1152/jn.90418.2008|issn=0022-3077|pmc=2604850|pmid=18842955}}</ref> In his recent labs, he has been studying the contributions of a third [[Neurotrophin-3|neurotrophin]] (NT-3) and what the effects are when the [[synapse]] that is involved in [[transmission]] between [[stretch receptor]]s and [[motor neuron]]s is altered.\n\nMendell's research on [[neuronal plasticity]] is specifically focused on the [[Spinal cord|mammalian spinal cord]]. He has combined some of his research from NT-3 to help show how neurotrophins can help alter the function of both damaged and undamaged neurons.\n\nMuch of the work Mendell has done with both neurotrophin and neuronal plasticity has some overlap into the realm of [[pain]], and what their roles are in both reducing and relieving pain. For example, Mendell has conducted research which has shown the relationship between [[nerve growth factor]]s (a type of neurotrophin) and inflammatory pain.\n\nMendell discovered the property of [[windup pain]] in the [[spinal cord]]. Windup is the property of [[Group C nerve fiber|C-fibres]] in the [[Peripheral nervous system|peripheral nerves]] of the spinal cord that when stimulated at repetitious low frequencies there will be a gradual accumulation in the amplitude of response.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolf|first=Clifford J.|date=August 1996|title=Windup and central sensitization are not equivalent|url=https://journals.lww.com/pain/Citation/1996/08000/Windup_and_central_sensitization_are_not.1.aspx|journal=PAIN|volume=66|issue=2|pages=105\u2013108|issn=0304-3959}}</ref>\n\nMendell has been interested in the role neurotrophins play in nervous plasticity since at least the mid 1990s. At the time, neurotrophins were understood to be significant factors in neuronal development and [[Differentiation (biology)|differentiation]] in the [[Central nervous system|central]] and [[peripheral nervous system]], however; scientists were still exploring the specific functions of individual neurotrophins. Subsequent findings suggested that neurotrophins have effects on both damaged and undamaged neurons. As such, neurotrophins are a major facet of [[spinal cord injury]] research. Mendell's research on neurotrophins has evolved synchronously with the understanding of neurotrophins. In more recent times, Mendell\u2019s research has been focused partly on spinal cord injury and the \t\n\n[[Hyperalgesia]], increase of sensitivity to a stimulus, was found by Mendell to be influenced by the introduction of [[nerve growth factor]], NGF. It functions by interactions with sensory [[Nociceptor|nociceptive]] neurons. Mendell was able to investigate how [[rodent]]s and [[mammal]]s sensitivity to thermal and mechanical stimulus was increased through exposure to NGF.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molliver|first=D. C|last2=Wright|first2=D. E|last3=Leitner|first3=M. L|last4=Parsadanian|first4=A. Sh|last5=Doster|first5=K|last6=Wen|first6=D|last7=Yan|first7=Q|last8=Snider|first8=W. D|date=1997-10-01|title=IB4-Binding DRG Neurons Switch from NGF to GDNF Dependence in Early Postnatal Life|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627300809666|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=19|issue=4|pages=849\u2013861|doi=10.1016/S0896-6273(00)80966-6|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> NGF was shown by Mendell to also play a role in the development of young mammals. Mature animals, he showed, that NGF had a possible role in the linkage of [[hyperalgesia]] and [[inflammation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.lww.com/anesthesia-analgesia/Fulltext/2007/09000/Pathophysiology_of_Peripheral_Neuropathic_Pain_.44.aspx|title=Pathophysiology of Peripheral Neuropathic Pain: Immune... : Anesthesia & Analgesia|website=LWW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Major works and contributions ==\nIn 1965, Mendell's doctoral dissertation was published in the academic journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''. The dissertation was about\u00a0how [[Group C nerve fiber|C fibres]] in the dorsal horn affect the A fibres. He concluded that his evidence did not support the idea that the firing of C fibres had an effect on the presynaptic hyperpolarization of the A fibres of the cats that were experimented on.\n\nIn April 2016, Mendell helped to publish a paper<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harrison|first=Benjamin J.|last2=Venkat|first2=Gayathri|last3=Lamb|first3=James L.|last4=Hutson|first4=Tom H.|last5=Drury|first5=Cassa|last6=Rau|first6=Kristofer K.|last7=Bunge|first7=Mary Barlett|last8=Mendell|first8=Lorne M.|last9=Gage|first9=Fred H.|last10=Johnson|first10=Richard D.|last11=Hill|first11=Caitlin E.|date=2016-04-13|title=The Adaptor Protein CD2AP Is a Coordinator of Neurotrophin Signaling-Mediated Axon Arbor Plasticity|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/36/15/4259|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=36|issue=15|pages=4259\u20134275|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2423-15.2016|issn=0270-6474|pmid=27076424}}</ref> that focused on the relationship between a protein called [[CD2AP]] and the plasticity of [[neuron]]s. It is known that the growth of an [[axon]] of a neuron helps with both the adaptive and maladaptive [[Neuroplasticity|plasticity]] within the [[nervous system]]. Therefore, if an axon becomes injured, or cannot function to its best ability, the consequences can be in the form of [[Neurological disorder|neurologic disease]]. The protein CD2AP in this study was looked at in depth, which is responsible for coordinating axon outgrowth. Mendell and his team were able to observe that CD2AP is amplified within [[dorsal root ganglion]]s (DRGs) during axonal sprouting, but decreases in quantity during axonal [[Regeneration (biology)|regeneration]]. Based on these findings, it is still undetermined what the exact relationship between the control of the regeneration of previously damaged axons and the additional development of non-damaged axons is.\n\nIn another one of his studies,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mantyh|first=Patrick W.|last2=Koltzenburg|first2=Martin|last3=Mendell|first3=Lorne M.|last4=Tive|first4=Leslie|last5=Shelton|first5=David L.|date=2011-07-01|title=Antagonism of Nerve Growth Factor-TrkA Signaling and the Relief of Pain|url=https://anesthesiology.pubs.asahq.org/article.aspx?articleid=1933906|journal=Anesthesiology: The Journal of the American Society of Anesthesiologists|language=en|volume=115|issue=1|pages=189\u2013204|doi=10.1097/ALN.0b013e31821b1ac5|issn=0003-3022}}</ref> conducted in July 2011, Mendell et al. looked at the mechanisms involved in the relationship between [[Nerve growth factor|neuronal growth factors]] (NGF), which is a [[neurotrophin]], and pain. It is known that specific mutations in NGF or [[Tropomyosin receptor kinase A|TrkA]] genes can lead to a decrease in the sensitivity to [[pain]]. However, the NGF-TrkA axis, on the other hand, can facilitate the development of many different types of long-term acute and [[chronic pain]]. With this, this study was able to conclude that one has to look at how many NGF-responsive (meaning how many are TrkA-positive) [[nociceptor]]s are actually connected to the tissue where the pain is coming from. This is an important relationship because the amount of [[Nerve|innervation]] widely varies between different types of tissue. Then, once this has been examined, one can more effectively choose which chronic pain state to target. Therefore, if it is able to be applied effectively, choosing therapies that rely on targeting NGF-TrkA signaling may represent a new way to treat different types of chronic pain.\n\nMendell has also put forth research<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Garc\u00eda-Al\u00edas|first=Guillermo|last2=Petrosyan|first2=Hayk A.|last3=Schnell|first3=Lisa|last4=Horner|first4=Philip J.|last5=Bowers|first5=William J.|last6=Mendell|first6=Lorne M.|last7=Fawcett|first7=James W.|last8=Arvanian|first8=Victor L.|date=2011-12-07|title=Chondroitinase ABC Combined with Neurotrophin NT-3 Secretion and NR2D Expression Promotes Axonal Plasticity and Functional Recovery in Rats with Lateral Hemisection of the Spinal Cord|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/31/49/17788|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=31|issue=49|pages=17788\u201317799|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4308-11.2011|issn=0270-6474|pmid=22159095}}</ref> about the increased possibility of promoting [[spinal cord]] repair through a combination of several different [[treatment]]s. The mechanisms involved in this are due to the additive effects when several different neurotrophins and [[protein]]s are combined, including [[Chondroitin ABC lyase|chondroitinase ABC]], [[Neurotrophin-3|NT3]], and enhanced levels of [[NR2D]]. These together allow for either the synthesis or strengthening of spinal circuits, as well as slight recovery of function for those that have been damaged.\n\n=== Positions held ===\n*Chair of the Department of Neurobiology and Behavior, [[Stony Brook University]], 1986-2006\n*''[[Journal of Neurophysiology]]'' editor-in-chief, 1983-1989\n*On the Editorial Board for the [[Journal of Neurophysiology]], current\n*On the Editorial Board for the [[The Journal of Neuroscience|Journal of Neuroscience]], 1983-1989\n*On the Council for the [[Society for Neuroscience]], 1986-1990\n*President of the Association of Neuroscience Departments and Programs, 1991-1992\n*Treasurer of the [[Society for Neuroscience]], 1996-1997\n*President of the [[Society for Neuroscience]], 1997-1998\n*[[Board of directors|Board of Directors]] for the Craig Neilsen Foundation, 2009\n*Chairman for the [[Spinal Cord Injury|Spinal Cord Injury Research Board]] of the State of New York, 2013\n*Senior Editor for [[Neuroplasticity]] for the [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] Press Research Encyclopedia in Neuroscience, 2015<ref name=\"renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu/neurobiology/honors|title=Awards and Honors {{!}} Renaissance School of Medicine at Stony Brook University|website=renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Honors and awards ===\n*Distinguished professor of Neurobiology and Behavior at [[Stony Brook University]]\n*Member of the London (UK) Pain Consortium Advisory Board, 2009-2014\n*Chosen to give the [[History of neuroscience|History of Neuroscience]] plenary lecture (\u201cThe Emergence of Contemporary Pain Neuroscience\u201d) during the Annual Meeting of the Society for Neuroscience, 2012 \n*Member of the International Science Advisory Council of Brain Canada, 2014\n*Named a fellow for the [[American Physiological Society]] Inaugural Class, 2015<ref name=\"renaissance.stonybrookmedicine.edu\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mendell, Lorne}}\n[[Category:Neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University School of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Stony Brook University faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "BISCquick", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResearch focus:minor edit for finishing section. Needs source?", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorne_Mendell"}
{"title_page": "Bob Weir", "text_new": "{{other uses|Robert Weir (disambiguation){{!}}Robert Weir}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Template:Infobox musical artist -->\n| name = Bob Weir\n| image = File:Bobweirlive2010.jpg\n| caption = Bob Weir performing in 2010\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Robert Hall Parber\n| alias = <!-- N/A -->\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1947|10|16}}\n| birth_place ={{nowrap|[[San Francisco, California]], U.S.}}\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[psychedelic rock]]\n* [[folk music|folk]]}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals}}\n| years_active = 1963\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n* [[Grateful Dead Records|Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]/[[Legacy Recordings|Legacy]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]]\n* [[Bobby and the Midnites]]\n* [[RatDog]]\n* [[The Other Ones]]\n* [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]]\n* [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\n* [[Dead & Company]]}}\n* [[Bob Weir and Wolf Bros]]\n| website = {{URL|http://bobweir.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Hall Weir''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u026a\u0259r}} {{respell|WEER|'}};<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Jerry Garcia and Bob Weir |year=1989 |title=TV ad for AIDS research donations |medium=Television |format=Advertisement |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=krUUrpScAuA}}</ref> born October 16, 1947) is an American musician and songwriter best known as a founding member of the [[rock music|rock]] band [[Grateful Dead]]. After the Grateful Dead disbanded in 1995,<ref>Selvin, Joel (December 9, 1995). [http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/PAGE-ONE-End-of-the-Road-for-Grateful-Dead-3017847.php \"End of the Road for Grateful Dead; Without Garcia, Band Just Can't Keep Truckin'\"], ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved July 1, 2015.</ref> Weir performed with [[The Other Ones]], later known as [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]], together with other former members of the Grateful Dead. Weir also founded and played in several other bands during and after his career with the Grateful Dead, including [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]], the Bob Weir Band, [[Bobby and the Midnites]], Scaring the Children, [[RatDog]], and [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]], which he co-led with former Grateful Dead bassist [[Phil Lesh]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/article/lesh-weir-russo-lane-chimenti-new-group-furthur-for-sept | title=Phil Lesh, Bob Weir, Joe Russo, Jay Lane, Jeff Chimenti and John Kadlecik Form New Band 'Furthur', Set Dates For September | work=[[JamBase]] | date=August 14, 2009}}</ref> In 2015, Weir, along with former [[Grateful Dead]] members [[Mickey Hart]] and [[Bill Kreutzmann]], joined with [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-winning singer/guitarist [[John Mayer]], bassist [[Oteil Burbridge]], and keyboardist [[Jeff Chimenti]] to form the band [[Dead & Company]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655898/grateful-dead-john-mayer-show-tour | title=The Grateful Dead Is Resurrected Once More, This Time with John Mayer: Exclusive | last=Halperin | first=Shirley | date=August 5, 2015 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref> The band remains active.\n\nDuring his career with the Grateful Dead, Weir played mostly [[rhythm guitar]] and sang many of the band's [[Rock and roll|rock-n-roll]] and [[Country music|country & western]] songs. In 1994, he was inducted into The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame as a member of the Grateful Dead.\n\n==Early life==\nWeir was born in [[San Francisco, California]] to John (Jack) Parber and a fellow college student, who later gave him up for adoption;<ref>Selvin, Joel (March 21, 2004). [http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Weir-finds-his-birth-father-and-adopts-a-vintage-2778049.php \"Weir Finds His Birth Father and Adopts a Vintage Guitar\"], ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved October 23, 2014.</ref> he was raised by his adoptive parents, Frederic Utter and Eleanor Cramer Weir, in the suburb of [[Atherton, California|Atherton]].<ref>Lesh, Phil (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=c8MtVkAglysC&pg=PT32&dq=frederick+eleanor+weir+%2B+grateful+dead&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6mxJVKC9LIeOyATIxoC4CQ&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=frederick%20eleanor%20weir%20%2B%20grateful%20dead&f=false ''Searching for the Sound: My Life with the Grateful Dead'']. Little, Brown and Company.  {{ISBN|978-0316009980}}. Retrieved October 23, 2014.</ref>  He began playing [[guitar]] at age thirteen after less successful experimentation with the [[piano]] and the [[trumpet]]. He had trouble in school because of undiagnosed [[dyslexia]] and he was expelled from nearly every school he attended, including [[Menlo-Atherton High School]] in Atherton<ref name=\"multiple\">McNally, Dennis. ''A Long Strange Trip: The Inside History of the Grateful Dead.'' New York: Broadway Books, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7679-1185-7}}</ref> and [[Fountain Valley School]] in Colorado, where he met future Grateful Dead lyricist [[John Perry Barlow]].<ref name=\"cpr.org\">{{cite web | url=https://www.cpr.org/news/videos-grateful-dead-guitarist-bob-weir-goes-back-fountain-valley-high | title=Videos: Grateful Dead Guitarist Bob Weir Goes Back To Fountain Valley High | author=Hart Van Denburg | date=June 23, 2016 | publisher=Colorado Public Radio}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOn New Year's Eve, 1963, 16-year-old Weir and an underage friend were wandering the back alleys of [[Palo Alto]], looking for a club that would admit them, when they heard banjo music. They followed the music to its source, Dana Morgan's Music Store. Here, a young [[Jerry Garcia]], oblivious to the date, was waiting for his students to arrive. Weir and Garcia spent the night playing music together and then decided to form a band. [[The Beatles]] significantly influenced their musical direction. \"The Beatles were why we turned from a [[jug band]] into a rock 'n' roll band,\" said Bob Weir. \"What we saw them doing was impossibly attractive. I couldn't think of anything else more worth doing.\"<ref>Jackson, Blair (2000). ''Garcia: An American Life'', p. 67</ref> Originally called Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions, the band was later renamed The Warlocks and eventually the [[Grateful Dead]].\n\n[[File:Bob Weir 1975.jpg|thumb|left|Weir performing with [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]], in 1975. Photo: [[David Gans (musician)|David Gans]]]]\nWeir played [[rhythm guitar]] and sang a large portion of the [[lead vocals]] through all of the Dead's 30-year career. In the fall of 1968, the Dead played some concerts without Weir and [[Ron \"Pigpen\" McKernan]]. These shows, with the band billed as \"Mickey and the Hartbeats\", were intermixed with full-lineup Grateful Dead concerts. In his biography of Jerry Garcia, Blair Jackson notes, \"Garcia and Lesh determined that Weir and Pigpen were not pulling their weight musically in the band\u2026  Most of the band fights at this time were about Bobby's guitar playing.\"<ref>Jackson, Blair (2000). ''Garcia: An American Life'', p. 155</ref> Late in the year, the band relented and took Weir and Pigpen back in full-time.<ref>McNally, p. 279, 284</ref><ref>Scott, John W. et al. (1999). ''DeadBase XI: The Complete Guide to Grateful Dead Song Lists'', DeadBase, {{ISBN|1-877657-22-0}}, p. 8</ref>\n\nThe incident apparently led to a period of significant growth in Weir's guitar playing.  Phil Lesh said that when drummer Mickey Hart left the band temporarily in early 1971, he was able to hear Weir's playing more clearly than ever and \"I found myself astonished, delighted and excited beyond measure at what Bobby was doing.\" Lesh described Weir's playing as \"quirky, whimsical and goofy\" and noted his ability to play chord [[Voicing (music)|voicings]] on the guitar (with only four fingers) that one would normally hear from a keyboard (with up to ten fingers).<ref>''Searching for the Sound'', Phil Lesh</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s, Weir began to experiment with [[slide guitar]] techniques and perform certain songs during Dead shows using the slide. His unique guitar style is strongly influenced by the hard bop pianist [[McCoy Tyner]] and he has cited artists as diverse as [[John Coltrane]], the [[Reverend Gary Davis|Rev. Gary Davis]], and [[Igor Stravinsky]] as influences.<ref name=multiple />\n\nWeir's first solo album ''[[Ace (Bob Weir album)|Ace]]'' appeared in 1972, with the Grateful Dead performing as the band on the album, though credited individually. Included in this line-up were [[Keith Godchaux]] and his wife [[Donna Godchaux|Donna]], both of whom would be in the band by the time of the album's release. A live version of the album's best-known song, \"Playing in the Band\", had been issued on the [[Grateful Dead (album)|''Skull & Roses'' album]] of the previous year. While continuing to perform as a member of the Grateful Dead, in 1975 and 1976 Weir played in the Bay Area band [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]] with friends [[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matt Kelly]] and [[Dave Torbert]]. He later contributed to Kelly's 1987 album ''A Wing and a Prayer'', on Relix Records. In 1978 he fronted the Bob Weir Band with [[Brent Mydland]], who joined the Grateful Dead the following year. In 1980 he formed another side band, [[Bobby and the Midnites]].\n\nShortly before Garcia's death in 1995, Weir formed another band, RatDog Revue, later shortened to [[RatDog]]. In RatDog, Weir performs covers of songs by various artists, including [[The Beatles]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Chuck Berry]], and [[Willie Dixon]] while also performing many Grateful Dead songs. In addition, Ratdog performs many of their own originals, most of which were released on the album ''[[Evening Moods]]''. \n[[File:Bob Weir Jay Lane RatDog 2009.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Weir and [[Jay Lane]] on stage with [[RatDog]] in 2009.]]\n\nWeir has participated in the various [[Reunions of the Grateful Dead|reformations of the Grateful Dead's members]], including 1998, 2000, and 2002 stints as [[The Other Ones]] and in 2003, 2004 and 2009 as [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]]. In 2008 he performed in the two [[Deadheads for Obama]] concerts. In 2009 Bob Weir and [[Phil Lesh]] formed a new band called [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\u2014so-named in honor of [[Ken Kesey]]'s famous psychedelically-painted bus.\n\nIn 2011, Weir founded the [[Tamalpais Research Institute]], also known as TRI Studios.  TRI is a high-tech recording studio and virtual music venue, used to stream live concerts over the internet in high-definition.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2011/06/07/DDV41JNL2U.DTL | title=Grateful Dead's Bob Weir debuts TRI Studios on Web | last=Selvin | first=Joel | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=June 7, 2011 | accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Weir toured with Chris Robinson of the [[Black Crowes]] and singer/songwriter [[Jackie Greene]] as the Weir, Robinson, & Greene Acoustic Trio.<ref>{{cite web | last=Herb | first=Bobby | url=https://americansongwriter.com/2012/06/wakarusa-report-weir-robinson-greene-acoustic-trio/ | title=Wakarusa Report: Weir, Robinson, & Greene Acoustic Trio | date=June 1, 2012 | work=[[American Songwriter]] | accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref>\n\nWeir resuscitated RatDog in March 2013. The RatDog Quartet, featuring Weir, [[Jay Lane]], [[Robin Sylvester]], and [[Jonathan Wilson (musician)|Jonathan Wilson]] debuted on March 3, at the Sweetwater Music Hall. [[Jason Crosby]] was their featured guest at the first two shows.\n\nOn April 25, 2013, Weir collapsed onstage during a Furthur performance at the Capitol Theater in Port Chester, New York. The band finished the show without him. He performed with the band two days later in Atlantic City, but on April 29 a representative announced that Weir would be \"unable to perform in any capacity for the next several weeks\" for unspecified reasons.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/furthur-cancel-bottlerock-festival-headline-slot-20130501 | title=Furthur Cancel BottleRock Festival Gig After Bob Weir's Stage Fall | first=Benjy | last=Eisen | date=May 1, 2013 | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> Weir resumed performing that summer.\n\nOn April 23, 2014, ''[[The Other One: The Long Strange Trip of Bob Weir]]'' premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] directed by [[Mike Fleiss]] husband of [[Miss America 2012]], [[Laura Kaeppeler]].<ref>[https://tribecafilm.com/filmguide/53208ad4c07f5df7d2000701-other-one-the-long-strang ''The Other One: The Long, Strange Trip of Bob Weir''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424202906/https://tribecafilm.com/filmguide/53208ad4c07f5df7d2000701-other-one-the-long-strang |date=April 24, 2014 }}, Tribeca Film Festival. Retrieved April 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2014, Weir abruptly canceled all of his upcoming appearances, according to The [[Huffington Post]], \"The cancellations include all shows for the rest of the year with his band [[Ratdog]], as well as a concert with [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/11/bob-weir-cancels_n_5667112.html | title=Bob Weir, Grateful Dead Co-Founder, Cancels All Concerts | first=Evan | last=Agostini | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=August 11, 2014 | accessdate=August 11, 2014}}</ref> According to [[Jambase]], Ratdog performed without Weir in Las Vegas in July 2014. \"A statement from the venue said Weir was 'under the weather.'\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/articles/122109/ratdog-plays-on-without-bob-weir-in-las-vegas | title=RatDog Plays On Without Bob Weir In Las Vegas | first=Scott | last=Bernstein | date=July 6, 2014 | publisher=[[Jambase]] | accessdate=August 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early July 2015, Weir joined the other original living members of the Grateful Dead \u2014Mickey Hart, Bill Kreutzmann, and Phil Lesh \u2014 for three shows at Soldier Field in Chicago. These four surviving members (known as the \"Core Four\") were joined by [[Jeff Chimenti]] on keys and [[Phish]]'s [[Trey Anastasio]] on lead guitar and shared vocals, and Bruce Hornsby on piano. The reunion was 20 years nearly to the day since the band's final concert with Jerry Garcia at the same venue in 1995. \"Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of Grateful Dead\" was billed as the original four members' last-ever performance together.  Based on demand, two additional Fare Thee Will concerts were added to the series, performed in late June 2015 at Levi Stadium in California. \n\nOn October 5, 2015, Weir performed with Ratdog at a special celebratory 60th Birthday Bash for [[Steve Kimock]], it was the first time Ratdog had performed again since the aforementioned cancellations of his 2014 summer tour.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-among-steve-kimocks-guests-at-birthday-bash | title=Bob Weir Among Steve Kimock's Guests At Birthday Bash | work=[[JamBase]] | first=Scott | last=Bernstein | date=October 6, 2015 | accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015 Weir teamed up with former Grateful Dead bandmates Mickey Hart and Billy Kreutzmann as well as guitarist [[John Mayer]], bassist [[Oteil Burbridge]] and keyboardist [[Jeff Chimenti]] to form [[Dead & Company]]. They played 22 shows starting at the end of October, concluding with a four show New Year's run including two shows in San Francisco and two in Los Angeles, ending with a three set show on New Year's Eve. The band continues to tour regularly.\n\nIn May, 2016, Weir was a guest speaker & performer for the second annual Einstein Gala, in Toronto, Canada,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.einsteingala.com | title=The Einstein Gala: May 16, 2016 at the Carlu | accessdate=December 9, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124165259/http://www.einsteingala.com/ | archive-date=January 24, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> an event honoring the legacy of [[Albert Einstein]] and new visionaries in the arts and sciences. Weir spoke about what science and innovation had meant to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cp24.com/video?clipId=871008&binId=1.1127694&playlistPageNum=1|title=Grateful Dead's Bob Weir visits CP24|website=Cp24.com|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> Weir performed a solo acoustic set, and was joined mid-set by guitarist Dan Kanter.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://liveforlivemusic.com/news/bob-weir-discusses-science-and-performs-acoustic-set-at-einstein-gala-watch/ | title=Bob Weir Discusses Science And Performs Acoustic Set At Einstein Gala | date=May 15, 2016 |website=LiveForLifeMusic.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a live recording of Weir performing with The National was included on the massive ''Day of the Dead''. Weir's 2012 collaboration with members of The National as part of The Bridge Session helped pave the way for the Grateful Dead tribute. <ref>Greenhaus, Mike https://relix.com/articles/detail/indie_is_dead_the_national_detail_day_of_the_dead_compilation/ Relix</ref>\n\nWeir also confirmed in an interview with [[The Guardian]] in May, 2016, that he was writing a book.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/may/18/grateful-dead-bob-weir-im-nowhere-near-done | title=The Grateful Dead's Bob Weir: 'I'm nowhere near done with our legacy' | first=Jared | last=Lindzon | date=18 May 2016 | website=Theguardian.com | accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Bob Weir and the Wolf Brothers 3-21-2019 St. Louis.jpg|thumb|Weir playing with the Wolf Brothers on March 21, 2019, at The Pageant in St. Louis, Missouri.]]\nIn June 2016, at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival|Bonnaroo Arts And Music Festival]], Weir received the first ever [[Les Paul|Les Paul Spirit Award]], from the Les Paul Foundation.<ref name=\"guitarworld.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.guitarworld.com/artist-news/bob-weir-receive-first-les-paul-spirit-award/29215 | title=Bob Weir to Receive First Les Paul Spirit Award | work=[[Guitar World]] | date=June 7, 2016}}</ref> \"I cannot think of anyone more fitting to be honored with the first annual Les Paul Spirit Award than Bob Weir. Not only is he an extraordinary talent who has given us an amazing array of legendary music, but he is an innovator who understands music, technologies and the spirit of Les Paul,\" said Michael Braunstein, executive director of the Les Paul Foundation. \"If Les were still alive today, I have absolutely no doubt that he and Bob would be experimenting together at [[TRI Studios]] or at Les's house and the results would be extraordinary.\"<ref name=\"guitarworld.com\"/>\n\nWeir received the 2016 [[Lifetime Achievement Award]] at the 2016 Americana Honors & Awards in [[Nashville, TN]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/bob-weir-to-receive-americana-lifetime-achievement-award-w437110 | title=Americana Honors Taps Bob Weir, Shawn Colvin for Lifetime Achievement | first=Jon | last=Freeman | date=August 30, 2016 | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Weir released a new album of \"cowboy songs\" titled ''[[Blue Mountain (Bob Weir album)|Blue Mountain]]''. The release was followed by [[Campfire Tour (Bob Weir Tour)|a tour]] beginning in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10157279379005442&set=a.174142875441.237168.785495441&type=3|title=Mark Hennagir|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> The album was inspired by his time working as a ranch hand in Wyoming, when he was fifteen years old.<ref name=\"mashable.com\">{{cite web | last=Anthony | first=Brian | url=http://mashable.com/2015/08/10/bob-weir-interview-axs-grateful-dead/#WwnXW2i2kGqb | title=Watch The Grateful Dead's Bob Weir tease new song from upcoming album | website=Mashable.com | date=2015-08-11 | accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring the spring of 2018, Weir performed a series of concerts with former Grateful Dead bassist [[Phil Lesh]].  The duo, with guest musicians, was billed as Bobby and Phil.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Jesse |last=Jarnow |date=March 5, 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/live-reviews/bob-weir-phil-lesh-trey-anastasio-radio-city-live-review-w517460 |title=Bob Weir and Phil Lesh Get Thrillingly Loose at New York Tour Openers |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWeir performed a concert tour in the Fall of 2018, as Bob Weir and Wolf Bros.  The band is a trio, with Weir on guitar and vocals, [[Don Was]] on upright bass, and [[Jay Lane]] on drums.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 3, 2018 |url=https://relix.com/news/detail/bob_weir_announces_fall_tour_with_wolf_bros_featuring_don_was_and_jay_lane/ |title=Bob Weir Announces Fall Tour with Wolf Bros Featuring Don Was and Jay Lane |website=Relix.com |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=August 3, 2018 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-wolf-bros-announce-2018-fall-tour |title=Bob Weir & Wolf Bros Announce 2018 Fall Tour |website=JamBase.com |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref>  They continued touring in the Spring of 2019 with twenty more shows.  <ref>{{cite web|title=Bob Weir & Wolf Bros Confirm Spring Tour 2019|url=https://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-wolf-bros-spring-tour-dates-2019|publisher=jambase.com|accessdate=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Bob Weir and Mickey Hart, Obama Inaugural.jpg|thumb|left|Bob Weir and [[Mickey Hart]] performing at the Mid-Atlantic Inaugural Ball during the [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|Inauguration of Barack Obama]], January 20, 2009.]]\n\nWeir remained single throughout his years with the Grateful Dead, although he lived for several years (1969\u20131975) with Frankie Hart. Hart had been a [[Go-go dancing|go-go dancer]] at the [[Peppermint Lounge]] in New York, had worked in [[Apple Records]] American marketing department, and had performed on the TV shows ''[[Hullabaloo (TV series)|Hullabaloo]]'' and ''[[Shindig!]]''. She was allegedly the inspiration for the [[Robert Hunter (lyricist)|Robert Hunter]], Bob Weir  song \"[[Sugar Magnolia]]\".<ref>{{Cite book | title=A Long Strange Trip: The Inside History of the Grateful Dead | last=McNally | first=Dennis | year=2002 | publisher=Broadway Books | location=New York | pages=[https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0/page/358 358]\u20139 | isbn=0-7679-1185-7 | url=https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0 | url-access=registration }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.litkicks.com/BarlowOnNeal | title=Cassidy's Tale | last=Barlow | first=John | authorlink=John Perry Barlow | date=November 3, 1994 | work=Literary Kicks | accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>  Weir made her acquaintance through Mickey Hart, who dated her briefly. He met her following her first Grateful Dead show in New York in 1968. Her real name at that time was Frankie Azzara (from a previous marriage), but used the [[stage name]] \"Frankie Hart\" (after apparently \"borrowing\" Hart's last name). Although she and Weir never married, she adopted his last name after moving in with him and was subsequently known as Frankie Weir.<ref name=\"multiple\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.litkicks.com/BarlowOnNeal | title=Cassidy's Tale | last=Barlow | first=John | authorlink=John Perry Barlow | date=November 3, 1994 | work=Literary Kicks | accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://lostlivedead.blogspot.com/2009/07/february-27-1971-fillmore-west-james.html | title=Live Lost Dead: February 27, 1971 Fillmore West: James and the Good Brothers with Jerry Garcia and Jack Casady | date=July 9, 2009 | website=Livelostdead.blogspot.com | accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://mizshelysspace.blogspot.com/2007/05/my-little-pop-quiz.html | title= The World According To Me: My Little Pop Quiz | date=May 12, 2007 | website=Mizshelysspace.blogspot.com | accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> \n\nOn July 15, 1999, Weir married Natascha M\u00fcnter in [[Mill Valley, California|Mill Valley]], California.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Weir-Girlfriend-Wed-2920271.php|title=Weir, Girlfriend Wed|last=Selvin|first=Joel|date=1999-07-17|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Together they have two daughters, Shala Monet Weir<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/parties/slideshow/San-Francisco-Debutante-Ball-2016-131356.php|title=San Francisco Debutante Ball 2016|date=2016-06-22|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> and Chloe Kaelia Weir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/04/25/showbiz/grateful-dead-bob-weir/index.html|title=The Grateful Dead and Bob Weir's long strange trip|last=Ganley|first=Doug|date=2014|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Bob Weir's sister-in law is [[Leilani Munter|Leilani M\u00fcnter]], a race car driver in the [[ARCA Racing Series]] circuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minnpost.com/sports/2016/04/fast-and-curious-meet-nascar-driving-anti-carbon-crusading-vegetarian-rochester/|title=Fast and curious: meet the NASCAR-driving, anti-carbon crusading vegetarian from Rochester|date=2016-04-05|website=MinnPost|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nWeir is on the board of directors of the [[Rex Foundation]], the Furthur Foundation, and [[HeadCount]].<ref>[http://furthur.org/ Furthur Foundation web site], accessed December 14, 2010</ref> He also is a member of the Advisory Board of the Jerry Garcia Foundation along with Peter Shapiro and Seth Rogin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jerrygarciafoundation.org/|title=Jerry Garcia Foundation|website=Jerrygarciafoundation.org|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> He is an honorary member of the board of directors of the environmental organization [[Rainforest Action Network]], along with [[Woody Harrelson]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], and [[John Densmore]]. He is also on the honorary board of directors of Little Kids Rock, a non-profit organization that provides free musical instruments and instruction to children in under-served public schools throughout the U.S.\n\n==Guitars==\n[[File:Weir, Bob (2007) 2.jpg|thumb|right|Weir onstage in 2007, playing a Modulus G3FH]]\nEarly pictures of The Warlocks in concert show him playing a [[Gretsch]] Duo-Jet,<ref>[http://www.classicrockpage.com/newslet/newsgrap/dec99/grate.gif&imgrefurl=http://www.classicrockpage.com/newslet/issues/deciss3.htm&h=144&w=220&sz=14&hl=en&start=4&tbnid=281di-Kd-S-e9M:&tbnh=70&tbnw=107&prev=/images%3Fq%3D%2522the%2Bwarlocks%2522%2B%2522grateful%2Bdead%2522%26svnum%3D10%26hl%3Den%26safe%3Doff%26client%3Dsafari%26rls%3Den%26sa%3DG Psychedelic News] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716044124/http://www.classicrockpage.com/newslet/newsgrap/dec99/grate.gif |date=July 16, 2006 }}</ref> and after the Warlocks became the Grateful Dead, Weir briefly played a [[Rickenbacker|Rickenbacker 365]], a Guild Starfire IV semi-hollowbody (with Garcia playing an identical cherry red Starfire IV, which appear very similar to the Gibson ES-335) as well as a [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] [[Telecaster]] before settling on a cherry red 1965 [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] [[Gibson ES-335|ES-335]] as his primary guitar for the following decade.<ref>Hunter, Robert, Stephen Peters, Chuck Wills, Dennis McNally. ''Grateful Dead: The Illustrated Trip''. DK ADULT; 1 Amer ed edition (October, 2003). {{ISBN|0-7894-9963-0}}</ref> Weir can also be seen playing a sunburst ES-335 in ''[[The Grateful Dead Movie]]'', filmed in October 1974. During the early 1970s, Weir also used a Gibson ES-345, a 1961 or 1962 [[Gibson SG]] and a black [[Gibson Les Paul]] of indeterminate age in 1971.\n\nIn 1974, Weir began working with Jeff Hasselberger at [[Ibanez]] to develop a custom instrument.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dozin.com/bobs/guitars/Ibanez/guitar.html | title=Bob Weir Model 2681 | website=Dozin.com | date= | accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> Weir began playing the Ibanez 2681 during the recording of ''[[Blues for Allah]]''; this was a testbed instrument with sliding pickups that Hasselberger used to develop several additional 2681s for use onstage, as well as Weir's custom \"Cowboy Fancy\" guitar, which he played from 1976 until the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dozin.com/bobs/interview/weir.html | title=Bob Weir Rhythm Ace | first=Jon | last=Sievert | website=Dozin.com | date=August 1981 | accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> Weir began using a [[Modulus Guitars|Modulus]] Blackknife at that point, and continued to play the Blackknife, along with a hybrid Modulus/Casio guitar for the \"Space\" segment of Grateful Dead concerts for the rest of that band's history. Weir's acoustic guitars include several [[C.F. Martin & Company|Martins]], a [[Guild Guitar Company|Guild]], an [[Ovation Guitar Company|Ovation]], and a line of [[Alvarez Guitars|Alvarez-Yairi]] signature models.\n\nWith his post-Grateful Dead bands, Weir has played a [[Modulus Guitars|Modulus]] G3FH custom, a Gibson ES-335, and a 1956 Fender Telecaster previously owned by James Louis Parber, his late half-brother.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dozin.com/bobs/tele.htm | title=Telecaster Story | first=Bob | last=Weir | website=Dozin.com | date= | accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Weir-finds-his-birth-father-and-adopts-a-vintage-2778049.php|title=Weir finds his birth father and adopts a vintage guitar|date=21 March 2004|website=Sfgate.com|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, during a preview of Weir's new solo album, ''Blue Mountain'', Weir stated that the only instrument he used during the recording of the album was a [[Martin Guitars|Martin]] acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-previews-blue-mountain-cowboy-album-campfire-tour-nyc-showcase | title=Bob Weir Previews 'Blue Mountain' Cowboy Album & Campfire Tour At NYC Showcase | first=Scott | last=Bernstein | date=August 5, 2016 | website=JamBase.com}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''With the Grateful Dead'''\n{{Main|Grateful Dead discography}}\n'''Solo albums'''\n* ''[[Ace (Bob Weir album)|Ace]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Heaven Help the Fool]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Weir Here \u2013 The Best of Bob Weir]]'' - compilation (2004)\n* ''[[Blue Mountain (Bob Weir album)|Blue Mountain]]'' (2016)\n\n'''with [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]]'''\n* ''[[Kingfish (1976 album)|Kingfish]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Live 'n' Kickin' (Kingfish album)|Live 'n' Kickin']]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Kingfish in Concert: King Biscuit Flower Hour]]'' (1996)\n\n'''with [[Bobby and the Midnites]]'''\n* ''[[Bobby and the Midnites (album)|Bobby and the Midnites]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Where the Beat Meets the Street]]''  (1984)\n\n'''with [[RatDog]]'''\n* ''[[Evening Moods]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Live at Roseland]]'' (2001)\n\n'''Collaborations'''\n* ''[[Live (Weir/Wasserman album)|Live]]'' - Bob Weir and Rob Wasserman (1998)\n* ''[[Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions (album)|Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions]]'' - Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions (1999)\n* ''[[Fall 1989: The Long Island Sound]]'' \u2013 Jerry Garcia Band and Bob Weir & Rob Wasserman (2013)\n* ''[[Gathering (Josh Ritter album)|Gathering]]'' \u2013 Josh Ritter (2017) \u2013 guest vocals\n\n'''Videos'''\n* ''[[Move Me Brightly]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The Other One: The Long Strange Trip of Bob Weir|The Other One: The Long, Strange Trip of Bob Weir]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Long Strange Trip]]'' (2017)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Condran, Ed. [https://archive.is/20130101181342/http://www.acweekly.com/view.php?id=11003 \"Hot Rats\"], ''[[Atlantic City Weekly]]'', July 9, 2009\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.rat-dog.com/ The official Bob Weir & RatDog site]\n* [http://www.bobweir.net/ The official Bob Weir site]\n* [https://archive.org/details/BobWeir Bob Weir collection] at the [[Internet Archive]]'s live music archive\n*[http://www.dead.net/band/bob-weir Bob Weir on the Grateful Dead's Official Site]\n\n{{Bob Weir}}\n{{Grateful Dead}}\n{{RatDog}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weir, Bob}}\n[[Category:Bob Weir| ]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:Grateful Dead members]]\n[[Category:Singers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk guitarists]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:People from Atherton, California]]\n[[Category:RatDog members]]\n[[Category:The Other Ones members]]\n[[Category:Furthur (band) members]]\n[[Category:Dead & Company members]]\n[[Category:Bobby and the Midnites members]]\n[[Category:Kingfish (band) members]]\n[[Category:Go Ahead (band) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Arista Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Robert Weir (disambiguation){{!}}Robert Weir}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Template:Infobox musical artist -->\n| name = Bob Weir\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = File:Bobweirlive2010.jpg\n| caption = Bob Weir performing in 2010\n| birth_name = Robert Hall Parber\n| alias = <!-- N/A -->\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1947|10|16}}\n| birth_place ={{nowrap|[[San Francisco, California]], U.S.}}\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[psychedelic rock]]\n* [[folk music|folk]]}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals}}\n| years_active = 1963\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n* [[Grateful Dead Records|Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]/[[Legacy Recordings|Legacy]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]]\n* [[Bobby and the Midnites]]\n* [[RatDog]]\n* [[The Other Ones]]\n* [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]]\n* [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\n* [[Dead & Company]]}}\n* [[Bob Weir and Wolf Bros]]\n| website = {{URL|http://bobweir.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Hall Weir''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u026a\u0259r}} {{respell|WEER|'}};<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Jerry Garcia and Bob Weir |year=1989 |title=TV ad for AIDS research donations |medium=Television |format=Advertisement |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=krUUrpScAuA}}</ref> born October 16, 1947) is an American musician and songwriter best known as a founding member of the [[rock music|rock]] band [[Grateful Dead]]. After the Grateful Dead disbanded in 1995,<ref>Selvin, Joel (December 9, 1995). [http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/PAGE-ONE-End-of-the-Road-for-Grateful-Dead-3017847.php \"End of the Road for Grateful Dead; Without Garcia, Band Just Can't Keep Truckin'\"], ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved July 1, 2015.</ref> Weir performed with [[The Other Ones]], later known as [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]], together with other former members of the Grateful Dead. Weir also founded and played in several other bands during and after his career with the Grateful Dead, including [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]], the Bob Weir Band, [[Bobby and the Midnites]], Scaring the Children, [[RatDog]], and [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]], which he co-led with former Grateful Dead bassist [[Phil Lesh]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/article/lesh-weir-russo-lane-chimenti-new-group-furthur-for-sept | title=Phil Lesh, Bob Weir, Joe Russo, Jay Lane, Jeff Chimenti and John Kadlecik Form New Band 'Furthur', Set Dates For September | work=[[JamBase]] | date=August 14, 2009}}</ref> In 2015, Weir, along with former [[Grateful Dead]] members [[Mickey Hart]] and [[Bill Kreutzmann]], joined with [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-winning singer/guitarist [[John Mayer]], bassist [[Oteil Burbridge]], and keyboardist [[Jeff Chimenti]] to form the band [[Dead & Company]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655898/grateful-dead-john-mayer-show-tour | title=The Grateful Dead Is Resurrected Once More, This Time with John Mayer: Exclusive | last=Halperin | first=Shirley | date=August 5, 2015 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref> The band remains active.\n\nDuring his career with the Grateful Dead, Weir played mostly [[rhythm guitar]] and sang many of the band's [[Rock and roll|rock-n-roll]] and [[Country music|country & western]] songs. In 1994, he was inducted into The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame as a member of the Grateful Dead.\n\n==Early life==\nWeir was born in [[San Francisco, California]] to John (Jack) Parber and a fellow college student, who later gave him up for adoption;<ref>Selvin, Joel (March 21, 2004). [http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Weir-finds-his-birth-father-and-adopts-a-vintage-2778049.php \"Weir Finds His Birth Father and Adopts a Vintage Guitar\"], ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved October 23, 2014.</ref> he was raised by his adoptive parents, Frederic Utter and Eleanor Cramer Weir, in the suburb of [[Atherton, California|Atherton]].<ref>Lesh, Phil (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=c8MtVkAglysC&pg=PT32&dq=frederick+eleanor+weir+%2B+grateful+dead&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6mxJVKC9LIeOyATIxoC4CQ&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=frederick%20eleanor%20weir%20%2B%20grateful%20dead&f=false ''Searching for the Sound: My Life with the Grateful Dead'']. Little, Brown and Company.  {{ISBN|978-0316009980}}. Retrieved October 23, 2014.</ref>  He began playing [[guitar]] at age thirteen after less successful experimentation with the [[piano]] and the [[trumpet]]. He had trouble in school because of undiagnosed [[dyslexia]] and he was expelled from nearly every school he attended, including [[Menlo-Atherton High School]] in Atherton<ref name=\"multiple\">McNally, Dennis. ''A Long Strange Trip: The Inside History of the Grateful Dead.'' New York: Broadway Books, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7679-1185-7}}</ref> and [[Fountain Valley School]] in Colorado, where he met future Grateful Dead lyricist [[John Perry Barlow]].<ref name=\"cpr.org\">{{cite web | url=https://www.cpr.org/news/videos-grateful-dead-guitarist-bob-weir-goes-back-fountain-valley-high | title=Videos: Grateful Dead Guitarist Bob Weir Goes Back To Fountain Valley High | author=Hart Van Denburg | date=June 23, 2016 | publisher=Colorado Public Radio}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOn New Year's Eve, 1963, 16-year-old Weir and an underage friend were wandering the back alleys of [[Palo Alto]], looking for a club that would admit them, when they heard banjo music. They followed the music to its source, Dana Morgan's Music Store. Here, a young [[Jerry Garcia]], oblivious to the date, was waiting for his students to arrive. Weir and Garcia spent the night playing music together and then decided to form a band. [[The Beatles]] significantly influenced their musical direction. \"The Beatles were why we turned from a [[jug band]] into a rock 'n' roll band,\" said Bob Weir. \"What we saw them doing was impossibly attractive. I couldn't think of anything else more worth doing.\"<ref>Jackson, Blair (2000). ''Garcia: An American Life'', p. 67</ref> Originally called Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions, the band was later renamed The Warlocks and eventually the [[Grateful Dead]].\n\n[[File:Bob Weir 1975.jpg|thumb|left|Weir performing with [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]], in 1975. Photo: [[David Gans (musician)|David Gans]]]]\nWeir played [[rhythm guitar]] and sang a large portion of the [[lead vocals]] through all of the Dead's 30-year career. In the fall of 1968, the Dead played some concerts without Weir and [[Ron \"Pigpen\" McKernan]]. These shows, with the band billed as \"Mickey and the Hartbeats\", were intermixed with full-lineup Grateful Dead concerts. In his biography of Jerry Garcia, Blair Jackson notes, \"Garcia and Lesh determined that Weir and Pigpen were not pulling their weight musically in the band\u2026  Most of the band fights at this time were about Bobby's guitar playing.\"<ref>Jackson, Blair (2000). ''Garcia: An American Life'', p. 155</ref> Late in the year, the band relented and took Weir and Pigpen back in full-time.<ref>McNally, p. 279, 284</ref><ref>Scott, John W. et al. (1999). ''DeadBase XI: The Complete Guide to Grateful Dead Song Lists'', DeadBase, {{ISBN|1-877657-22-0}}, p. 8</ref>\n\nThe incident apparently led to a period of significant growth in Weir's guitar playing.  Phil Lesh said that when drummer Mickey Hart left the band temporarily in early 1971, he was able to hear Weir's playing more clearly than ever and \"I found myself astonished, delighted and excited beyond measure at what Bobby was doing.\" Lesh described Weir's playing as \"quirky, whimsical and goofy\" and noted his ability to play chord [[Voicing (music)|voicings]] on the guitar (with only four fingers) that one would normally hear from a keyboard (with up to ten fingers).<ref>''Searching for the Sound'', Phil Lesh</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s, Weir began to experiment with [[slide guitar]] techniques and perform certain songs during Dead shows using the slide. His unique guitar style is strongly influenced by the hard bop pianist [[McCoy Tyner]] and he has cited artists as diverse as [[John Coltrane]], the [[Reverend Gary Davis|Rev. Gary Davis]], and [[Igor Stravinsky]] as influences.<ref name=multiple />\n\nWeir's first solo album ''[[Ace (Bob Weir album)|Ace]]'' appeared in 1972, with the Grateful Dead performing as the band on the album, though credited individually. Included in this line-up were [[Keith Godchaux]] and his wife [[Donna Godchaux|Donna]], both of whom would be in the band by the time of the album's release. A live version of the album's best-known song, \"Playing in the Band\", had been issued on the [[Grateful Dead (album)|''Skull & Roses'' album]] of the previous year. While continuing to perform as a member of the Grateful Dead, in 1975 and 1976 Weir played in the Bay Area band [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]] with friends [[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matt Kelly]] and [[Dave Torbert]]. He later contributed to Kelly's 1987 album ''A Wing and a Prayer'', on Relix Records. In 1978 he fronted the Bob Weir Band with [[Brent Mydland]], who joined the Grateful Dead the following year. In 1980 he formed another side band, [[Bobby and the Midnites]].\n\nShortly before Garcia's death in 1995, Weir formed another band, RatDog Revue, later shortened to [[RatDog]]. In RatDog, Weir performs covers of songs by various artists, including [[The Beatles]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Chuck Berry]], and [[Willie Dixon]] while also performing many Grateful Dead songs. In addition, Ratdog performs many of their own originals, most of which were released on the album ''[[Evening Moods]]''. \n[[File:Bob Weir Jay Lane RatDog 2009.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Weir and [[Jay Lane]] on stage with [[RatDog]] in 2009.]]\n\nWeir has participated in the various [[Reunions of the Grateful Dead|reformations of the Grateful Dead's members]], including 1998, 2000, and 2002 stints as [[The Other Ones]] and in 2003, 2004 and 2009 as [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]]. In 2008 he performed in the two [[Deadheads for Obama]] concerts. In 2009 Bob Weir and [[Phil Lesh]] formed a new band called [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\u2014so-named in honor of [[Ken Kesey]]'s famous psychedelically-painted bus.\n\nIn 2011, Weir founded the [[Tamalpais Research Institute]], also known as TRI Studios.  TRI is a high-tech recording studio and virtual music venue, used to stream live concerts over the internet in high-definition.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2011/06/07/DDV41JNL2U.DTL | title=Grateful Dead's Bob Weir debuts TRI Studios on Web | last=Selvin | first=Joel | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=June 7, 2011 | accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Weir toured with Chris Robinson of the [[Black Crowes]] and singer/songwriter [[Jackie Greene]] as the Weir, Robinson, & Greene Acoustic Trio.<ref>{{cite web | last=Herb | first=Bobby | url=https://americansongwriter.com/2012/06/wakarusa-report-weir-robinson-greene-acoustic-trio/ | title=Wakarusa Report: Weir, Robinson, & Greene Acoustic Trio | date=June 1, 2012 | work=[[American Songwriter]] | accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref>\n\nWeir resuscitated RatDog in March 2013. The RatDog Quartet, featuring Weir, [[Jay Lane]], [[Robin Sylvester]], and [[Jonathan Wilson (musician)|Jonathan Wilson]] debuted on March 3, at the Sweetwater Music Hall. [[Jason Crosby]] was their featured guest at the first two shows.\n\nOn April 25, 2013, Weir collapsed onstage during a Furthur performance at the Capitol Theater in Port Chester, New York. The band finished the show without him. He performed with the band two days later in Atlantic City, but on April 29 a representative announced that Weir would be \"unable to perform in any capacity for the next several weeks\" for unspecified reasons.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/furthur-cancel-bottlerock-festival-headline-slot-20130501 | title=Furthur Cancel BottleRock Festival Gig After Bob Weir's Stage Fall | first=Benjy | last=Eisen | date=May 1, 2013 | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> Weir resumed performing that summer.\n\nOn April 23, 2014, ''[[The Other One: The Long Strange Trip of Bob Weir]]'' premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] directed by [[Mike Fleiss]] husband of [[Miss America 2012]], [[Laura Kaeppeler]].<ref>[https://tribecafilm.com/filmguide/53208ad4c07f5df7d2000701-other-one-the-long-strang ''The Other One: The Long, Strange Trip of Bob Weir''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424202906/https://tribecafilm.com/filmguide/53208ad4c07f5df7d2000701-other-one-the-long-strang |date=April 24, 2014 }}, Tribeca Film Festival. Retrieved April 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2014, Weir abruptly canceled all of his upcoming appearances, according to The [[Huffington Post]], \"The cancellations include all shows for the rest of the year with his band [[Ratdog]], as well as a concert with [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/11/bob-weir-cancels_n_5667112.html | title=Bob Weir, Grateful Dead Co-Founder, Cancels All Concerts | first=Evan | last=Agostini | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=August 11, 2014 | accessdate=August 11, 2014}}</ref> According to [[Jambase]], Ratdog performed without Weir in Las Vegas in July 2014. \"A statement from the venue said Weir was 'under the weather.'\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/articles/122109/ratdog-plays-on-without-bob-weir-in-las-vegas | title=RatDog Plays On Without Bob Weir In Las Vegas | first=Scott | last=Bernstein | date=July 6, 2014 | publisher=[[Jambase]] | accessdate=August 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early July 2015, Weir joined the other original living members of the Grateful Dead \u2014Mickey Hart, Bill Kreutzmann, and Phil Lesh \u2014 for three shows at Soldier Field in Chicago. These four surviving members (known as the \"Core Four\") were joined by [[Jeff Chimenti]] on keys and [[Phish]]'s [[Trey Anastasio]] on lead guitar and shared vocals, and Bruce Hornsby on piano. The reunion was 20 years nearly to the day since the band's final concert with Jerry Garcia at the same venue in 1995. \"Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of Grateful Dead\" was billed as the original four members' last-ever performance together.  Based on demand, two additional Fare Thee Will concerts were added to the series, performed in late June 2015 at Levi Stadium in California. \n\nOn October 5, 2015, Weir performed with Ratdog at a special celebratory 60th Birthday Bash for [[Steve Kimock]], it was the first time Ratdog had performed again since the aforementioned cancellations of his 2014 summer tour.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-among-steve-kimocks-guests-at-birthday-bash | title=Bob Weir Among Steve Kimock's Guests At Birthday Bash | work=[[JamBase]] | first=Scott | last=Bernstein | date=October 6, 2015 | accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015 Weir teamed up with former Grateful Dead bandmates Mickey Hart and Billy Kreutzmann as well as guitarist [[John Mayer]], bassist [[Oteil Burbridge]] and keyboardist [[Jeff Chimenti]] to form [[Dead & Company]]. They played 22 shows starting at the end of October, concluding with a four show New Year's run including two shows in San Francisco and two in Los Angeles, ending with a three set show on New Year's Eve. The band continues to tour regularly.\n\nIn May, 2016, Weir was a guest speaker & performer for the second annual Einstein Gala, in Toronto, Canada,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.einsteingala.com | title=The Einstein Gala: May 16, 2016 at the Carlu | accessdate=December 9, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124165259/http://www.einsteingala.com/ | archive-date=January 24, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> an event honoring the legacy of [[Albert Einstein]] and new visionaries in the arts and sciences. Weir spoke about what science and innovation had meant to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cp24.com/video?clipId=871008&binId=1.1127694&playlistPageNum=1|title=Grateful Dead's Bob Weir visits CP24|website=Cp24.com|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> Weir performed a solo acoustic set, and was joined mid-set by guitarist Dan Kanter.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://liveforlivemusic.com/news/bob-weir-discusses-science-and-performs-acoustic-set-at-einstein-gala-watch/ | title=Bob Weir Discusses Science And Performs Acoustic Set At Einstein Gala | date=May 15, 2016 |website=LiveForLifeMusic.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a live recording of Weir performing with The National was included on the massive ''Day of the Dead''. Weir's 2012 collaboration with members of The National as part of The Bridge Session helped pave the way for the Grateful Dead tribute. <ref>Greenhaus, Mike https://relix.com/articles/detail/indie_is_dead_the_national_detail_day_of_the_dead_compilation/ Relix</ref>\n\nWeir also confirmed in an interview with [[The Guardian]] in May, 2016, that he was writing a book.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/may/18/grateful-dead-bob-weir-im-nowhere-near-done | title=The Grateful Dead's Bob Weir: 'I'm nowhere near done with our legacy' | first=Jared | last=Lindzon | date=18 May 2016 | website=Theguardian.com | accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Bob Weir and the Wolf Brothers 3-21-2019 St. Louis.jpg|thumb|Weir playing with the Wolf Brothers on March 21, 2019, at The Pageant in St. Louis, Missouri.]]\nIn June 2016, at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival|Bonnaroo Arts And Music Festival]], Weir received the first ever [[Les Paul|Les Paul Spirit Award]], from the Les Paul Foundation.<ref name=\"guitarworld.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.guitarworld.com/artist-news/bob-weir-receive-first-les-paul-spirit-award/29215 | title=Bob Weir to Receive First Les Paul Spirit Award | work=[[Guitar World]] | date=June 7, 2016}}</ref> \"I cannot think of anyone more fitting to be honored with the first annual Les Paul Spirit Award than Bob Weir. Not only is he an extraordinary talent who has given us an amazing array of legendary music, but he is an innovator who understands music, technologies and the spirit of Les Paul,\" said Michael Braunstein, executive director of the Les Paul Foundation. \"If Les were still alive today, I have absolutely no doubt that he and Bob would be experimenting together at [[TRI Studios]] or at Les's house and the results would be extraordinary.\"<ref name=\"guitarworld.com\"/>\n\nWeir received the 2016 [[Lifetime Achievement Award]] at the 2016 Americana Honors & Awards in [[Nashville, TN]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/bob-weir-to-receive-americana-lifetime-achievement-award-w437110 | title=Americana Honors Taps Bob Weir, Shawn Colvin for Lifetime Achievement | first=Jon | last=Freeman | date=August 30, 2016 | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Weir released a new album of \"cowboy songs\" titled ''[[Blue Mountain (Bob Weir album)|Blue Mountain]]''. The release was followed by [[Campfire Tour (Bob Weir Tour)|a tour]] beginning in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10157279379005442&set=a.174142875441.237168.785495441&type=3|title=Mark Hennagir|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> The album was inspired by his time working as a ranch hand in Wyoming, when he was fifteen years old.<ref name=\"mashable.com\">{{cite web | last=Anthony | first=Brian | url=http://mashable.com/2015/08/10/bob-weir-interview-axs-grateful-dead/#WwnXW2i2kGqb | title=Watch The Grateful Dead's Bob Weir tease new song from upcoming album | website=Mashable.com | date=2015-08-11 | accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring the spring of 2018, Weir performed a series of concerts with former Grateful Dead bassist [[Phil Lesh]].  The duo, with guest musicians, was billed as Bobby and Phil.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Jesse |last=Jarnow |date=March 5, 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/live-reviews/bob-weir-phil-lesh-trey-anastasio-radio-city-live-review-w517460 |title=Bob Weir and Phil Lesh Get Thrillingly Loose at New York Tour Openers |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWeir performed a concert tour in the Fall of 2018, as Bob Weir and Wolf Bros.  The band is a trio, with Weir on guitar and vocals, [[Don Was]] on upright bass, and [[Jay Lane]] on drums.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 3, 2018 |url=https://relix.com/news/detail/bob_weir_announces_fall_tour_with_wolf_bros_featuring_don_was_and_jay_lane/ |title=Bob Weir Announces Fall Tour with Wolf Bros Featuring Don Was and Jay Lane |website=Relix.com |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=August 3, 2018 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-wolf-bros-announce-2018-fall-tour |title=Bob Weir & Wolf Bros Announce 2018 Fall Tour |website=JamBase.com |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref>  They continued touring in the Spring of 2019 with twenty more shows.  <ref>{{cite web|title=Bob Weir & Wolf Bros Confirm Spring Tour 2019|url=https://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-wolf-bros-spring-tour-dates-2019|publisher=jambase.com|accessdate=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Bob Weir and Mickey Hart, Obama Inaugural.jpg|thumb|left|Bob Weir and [[Mickey Hart]] performing at the Mid-Atlantic Inaugural Ball during the [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|Inauguration of Barack Obama]], January 20, 2009.]]\n\nWeir remained single throughout his years with the Grateful Dead, although he lived for several years (1969\u20131975) with Frankie Hart. Hart had been a [[Go-go dancing|go-go dancer]] at the [[Peppermint Lounge]] in New York, had worked in [[Apple Records]] American marketing department, and had performed on the TV shows ''[[Hullabaloo (TV series)|Hullabaloo]]'' and ''[[Shindig!]]''. She was allegedly the inspiration for the [[Robert Hunter (lyricist)|Robert Hunter]], Bob Weir  song \"[[Sugar Magnolia]]\".<ref>{{Cite book | title=A Long Strange Trip: The Inside History of the Grateful Dead | last=McNally | first=Dennis | year=2002 | publisher=Broadway Books | location=New York | pages=[https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0/page/358 358]\u20139 | isbn=0-7679-1185-7 | url=https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0 | url-access=registration }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.litkicks.com/BarlowOnNeal | title=Cassidy's Tale | last=Barlow | first=John | authorlink=John Perry Barlow | date=November 3, 1994 | work=Literary Kicks | accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>  Weir made her acquaintance through Mickey Hart, who dated her briefly. He met her following her first Grateful Dead show in New York in 1968. Her real name at that time was Frankie Azzara (from a previous marriage), but used the [[stage name]] \"Frankie Hart\" (after apparently \"borrowing\" Hart's last name). Although she and Weir never married, she adopted his last name after moving in with him and was subsequently known as Frankie Weir.<ref name=\"multiple\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.litkicks.com/BarlowOnNeal | title=Cassidy's Tale | last=Barlow | first=John | authorlink=John Perry Barlow | date=November 3, 1994 | work=Literary Kicks | accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://lostlivedead.blogspot.com/2009/07/february-27-1971-fillmore-west-james.html | title=Live Lost Dead: February 27, 1971 Fillmore West: James and the Good Brothers with Jerry Garcia and Jack Casady | date=July 9, 2009 | website=Livelostdead.blogspot.com | accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://mizshelysspace.blogspot.com/2007/05/my-little-pop-quiz.html | title= The World According To Me: My Little Pop Quiz | date=May 12, 2007 | website=Mizshelysspace.blogspot.com | accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> \n\nOn July 15, 1999, Weir married Natascha M\u00fcnter in [[Mill Valley, California|Mill Valley]], California.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Weir-Girlfriend-Wed-2920271.php|title=Weir, Girlfriend Wed|last=Selvin|first=Joel|date=1999-07-17|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Together they have two daughters, Shala Monet Weir<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/parties/slideshow/San-Francisco-Debutante-Ball-2016-131356.php|title=San Francisco Debutante Ball 2016|date=2016-06-22|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> and Chloe Kaelia Weir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/04/25/showbiz/grateful-dead-bob-weir/index.html|title=The Grateful Dead and Bob Weir's long strange trip|last=Ganley|first=Doug|date=2014|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Bob Weir's sister-in law is [[Leilani Munter|Leilani M\u00fcnter]], a race car driver in the [[ARCA Racing Series]] circuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minnpost.com/sports/2016/04/fast-and-curious-meet-nascar-driving-anti-carbon-crusading-vegetarian-rochester/|title=Fast and curious: meet the NASCAR-driving, anti-carbon crusading vegetarian from Rochester|date=2016-04-05|website=MinnPost|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nWeir is on the board of directors of the [[Rex Foundation]], the Furthur Foundation, and [[HeadCount]].<ref>[http://furthur.org/ Furthur Foundation web site], accessed December 14, 2010</ref> He also is a member of the Advisory Board of the Jerry Garcia Foundation along with Peter Shapiro and Seth Rogin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jerrygarciafoundation.org/|title=Jerry Garcia Foundation|website=Jerrygarciafoundation.org|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> He is an honorary member of the board of directors of the environmental organization [[Rainforest Action Network]], along with [[Woody Harrelson]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], and [[John Densmore]]. He is also on the honorary board of directors of Little Kids Rock, a non-profit organization that provides free musical instruments and instruction to children in under-served public schools throughout the U.S.\n\n==Guitars==\n[[File:Weir, Bob (2007) 2.jpg|thumb|right|Weir onstage in 2007, playing a Modulus G3FH]]\nEarly pictures of The Warlocks in concert show him playing a [[Gretsch]] Duo-Jet,<ref>[http://www.classicrockpage.com/newslet/newsgrap/dec99/grate.gif&imgrefurl=http://www.classicrockpage.com/newslet/issues/deciss3.htm&h=144&w=220&sz=14&hl=en&start=4&tbnid=281di-Kd-S-e9M:&tbnh=70&tbnw=107&prev=/images%3Fq%3D%2522the%2Bwarlocks%2522%2B%2522grateful%2Bdead%2522%26svnum%3D10%26hl%3Den%26safe%3Doff%26client%3Dsafari%26rls%3Den%26sa%3DG Psychedelic News] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716044124/http://www.classicrockpage.com/newslet/newsgrap/dec99/grate.gif |date=July 16, 2006 }}</ref> and after the Warlocks became the Grateful Dead, Weir briefly played a [[Rickenbacker|Rickenbacker 365]], a Guild Starfire IV semi-hollowbody (with Garcia playing an identical cherry red Starfire IV, which appear very similar to the Gibson ES-335) as well as a [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] [[Telecaster]] before settling on a cherry red 1965 [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] [[Gibson ES-335|ES-335]] as his primary guitar for the following decade.<ref>Hunter, Robert, Stephen Peters, Chuck Wills, Dennis McNally. ''Grateful Dead: The Illustrated Trip''. DK ADULT; 1 Amer ed edition (October, 2003). {{ISBN|0-7894-9963-0}}</ref> Weir can also be seen playing a sunburst ES-335 in ''[[The Grateful Dead Movie]]'', filmed in October 1974. During the early 1970s, Weir also used a Gibson ES-345, a 1961 or 1962 [[Gibson SG]] and a black [[Gibson Les Paul]] of indeterminate age in 1971.\n\nIn 1974, Weir began working with Jeff Hasselberger at [[Ibanez]] to develop a custom instrument.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dozin.com/bobs/guitars/Ibanez/guitar.html | title=Bob Weir Model 2681 | website=Dozin.com | date= | accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> Weir began playing the Ibanez 2681 during the recording of ''[[Blues for Allah]]''; this was a testbed instrument with sliding pickups that Hasselberger used to develop several additional 2681s for use onstage, as well as Weir's custom \"Cowboy Fancy\" guitar, which he played from 1976 until the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dozin.com/bobs/interview/weir.html | title=Bob Weir Rhythm Ace | first=Jon | last=Sievert | website=Dozin.com | date=August 1981 | accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> Weir began using a [[Modulus Guitars|Modulus]] Blackknife at that point, and continued to play the Blackknife, along with a hybrid Modulus/Casio guitar for the \"Space\" segment of Grateful Dead concerts for the rest of that band's history. Weir's acoustic guitars include several [[C.F. Martin & Company|Martins]], a [[Guild Guitar Company|Guild]], an [[Ovation Guitar Company|Ovation]], and a line of [[Alvarez Guitars|Alvarez-Yairi]] signature models.\n\nWith his post-Grateful Dead bands, Weir has played a [[Modulus Guitars|Modulus]] G3FH custom, a Gibson ES-335, and a 1956 Fender Telecaster previously owned by James Louis Parber, his late half-brother.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dozin.com/bobs/tele.htm | title=Telecaster Story | first=Bob | last=Weir | website=Dozin.com | date= | accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Weir-finds-his-birth-father-and-adopts-a-vintage-2778049.php|title=Weir finds his birth father and adopts a vintage guitar|date=21 March 2004|website=Sfgate.com|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, during a preview of Weir's new solo album, ''Blue Mountain'', Weir stated that the only instrument he used during the recording of the album was a [[Martin Guitars|Martin]] acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/article/bob-weir-previews-blue-mountain-cowboy-album-campfire-tour-nyc-showcase | title=Bob Weir Previews 'Blue Mountain' Cowboy Album & Campfire Tour At NYC Showcase | first=Scott | last=Bernstein | date=August 5, 2016 | website=JamBase.com}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''With the Grateful Dead'''\n{{Main|Grateful Dead discography}}\n'''Solo albums'''\n* ''[[Ace (Bob Weir album)|Ace]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Heaven Help the Fool]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Weir Here \u2013 The Best of Bob Weir]]'' - compilation (2004)\n* ''[[Blue Mountain (Bob Weir album)|Blue Mountain]]'' (2016)\n\n'''with [[Kingfish (band)|Kingfish]]'''\n* ''[[Kingfish (1976 album)|Kingfish]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Live 'n' Kickin' (Kingfish album)|Live 'n' Kickin']]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Kingfish in Concert: King Biscuit Flower Hour]]'' (1996)\n\n'''with [[Bobby and the Midnites]]'''\n* ''[[Bobby and the Midnites (album)|Bobby and the Midnites]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Where the Beat Meets the Street]]''  (1984)\n\n'''with [[RatDog]]'''\n* ''[[Evening Moods]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Live at Roseland]]'' (2001)\n\n'''Collaborations'''\n* ''[[Live (Weir/Wasserman album)|Live]]'' - Bob Weir and Rob Wasserman (1998)\n* ''[[Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions (album)|Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions]]'' - Mother McCree's Uptown Jug Champions (1999)\n* ''[[Fall 1989: The Long Island Sound]]'' \u2013 Jerry Garcia Band and Bob Weir & Rob Wasserman (2013)\n* ''[[Gathering (Josh Ritter album)|Gathering]]'' \u2013 Josh Ritter (2017) \u2013 guest vocals\n\n'''Videos'''\n* ''[[Move Me Brightly]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The Other One: The Long Strange Trip of Bob Weir|The Other One: The Long, Strange Trip of Bob Weir]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Long Strange Trip]]'' (2017)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Condran, Ed. [https://archive.is/20130101181342/http://www.acweekly.com/view.php?id=11003 \"Hot Rats\"], ''[[Atlantic City Weekly]]'', July 9, 2009\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.rat-dog.com/ The official Bob Weir & RatDog site]\n* [http://www.bobweir.net/ The official Bob Weir site]\n* [https://archive.org/details/BobWeir Bob Weir collection] at the [[Internet Archive]]'s live music archive\n*[http://www.dead.net/band/bob-weir Bob Weir on the Grateful Dead's Official Site]\n\n{{Bob Weir}}\n{{Grateful Dead}}\n{{RatDog}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weir, Bob}}\n[[Category:Bob Weir| ]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category